WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
[Amit Varma]: One of my favorite poems is a miniature masterpiece that goes like this.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Separation, by W.S.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Mervyn.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Your absence has gone through me like thread through a needle.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:19.880
[Amit Varma]: Everything I do is stitched with its color.

00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:20.880
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:24.400
[Amit Varma]: While recording the episode you're going to hear now, it struck me that Mervyn's evocative

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:28.400
[Amit Varma]: poem is not just true of personal relationships.

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:31.960
[Amit Varma]: Relationships and societies can be haunted by the past in quite the same way.

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:35.520
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, you can look at the world through the prism of the seen and the unseen.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:39.520
[Amit Varma]: All the events that happen around you are what is seen, but the many layers of history

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:43.400
[Amit Varma]: that have led to them and that affect all our actions are unseen.

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:47.740
[Amit Varma]: This is true, especially for India, a complex country with complex histories.

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:52.820
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, everything that happens here is stitched with the color of the past.

00:00:52.820 --> 00:00:57.100
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that I have realized about India's partition is that it was not

00:00:57.100 --> 00:01:01.520
[Amit Varma]: just an event that unfolded over a couple of weeks or a couple of months or even a couple

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:02.520
[Amit Varma]: of years.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:08.400
[Amit Varma]: Instead, it lives on today and its consequences are all around us.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:16.120
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:17.120
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:20.120
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:24.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:28.320
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Aanchal Malhotra, an artist, historian and writer.

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:33.760
[Amit Varma]: A few years ago, Aanchal set out on a project to document oral histories of partition using

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:37.960
[Amit Varma]: the catalyst of physical objects that people carried with them on their trips from one

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:39.960
[Amit Varma]: side of the border to another.

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:44.960
[Amit Varma]: Simply put, she would meet survivors of partition, get them to show objects from their past life,

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:49.440
[Amit Varma]: and through that, open up this deep well of experiences and memories.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.320
[Amit Varma]: This came together in a remarkable and deeply moving book called Remnants of a Separation,

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:56.920
[Amit Varma]: published in the rest of the world as Remnants of Partition.

00:01:56.920 --> 00:02:02.680
[Amit Varma]: Aanchal is also the co-founder of the Museum of Material Memory, which she describes as

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:07.980
[Amit Varma]: quote, a digital repository of material culture of the Indian subcontinent, tracing family

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:12.760
[Amit Varma]: histories and social ethnography through heirlooms, collectibles and objects of antiquity.

00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:13.760
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:18.000
[Amit Varma]: I found this entire project so fascinating and even heartbreaking because while so much

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.760
[Amit Varma]: history can seem abstract, she made it concrete by giving us intimate details of personal

00:02:22.760 --> 00:02:29.040
[Amit Varma]: stories, which added so much depth to my understanding of the horror of those times and also of human

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:31.160
[Amit Varma]: nature and the human condition.

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:35.400
[Amit Varma]: When the lives of others come alive for us, then our own lives are enriched.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:39.480
[Amit Varma]: I learned a lot from this conversation with Aanchal, but before we get to that, let's

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:49.480
[Amit Varma]: take a quick commercial break.

