00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:05.560
[Guest]: Anshul, welcome to the seen and the unseen. Thank you. It's a pleasure to be here, Amit.

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:11.600
[Amit Varma]: Anshul, the shoe is really on the other foot now because instead of you asking other people about their past,

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:15.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to start asking you about your past. So tell me a little bit about

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:22.160
[Amit Varma]: yourself and how you came to doing what you're doing, you know, being a chronicler of memory as it were, a historian of sorts.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:26.720
[Amit Varma]: How did all this sort of, what are the different strands in your life which brought you here?

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:32.800
[Guest]: Well, I started any form of career that I had by being an artist.

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:38.320
[Guest]: And I don't know how many people know this, but I trained to be a traditional printmaker,

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:48.800
[Guest]: more specifically a metal engraver. So for, I guess, from the age of 17 to 26 or so, I worked in a print shop and

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.760
[Guest]: worked with copper plates and acid.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:58.640
[Guest]: And I really thought that that was, that was the direction that my life was going to remain in.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:06.080
[Guest]: Because ever since I've been young, I've been, I've only been fond of the arts and I have been lucky enough to have a family that supports that.

00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:16.480
[Guest]: So I did my BFA in traditional print and art history, then I did my MFA in printmaking, and I really thought that it would lead to a career in

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:19.040
[Guest]: what is basically a master printer.

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:29.120
[Guest]: And I think also the craft of printmaking is such an obsolete craft that what I loved about it is that I was associating myself to a kind of

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:35.600
[Guest]: almost forgotten history, whether it is, you know, printing on a printing press or setting handset type.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:41.520
[Guest]: And that was lovely. That was really lovely. But I do realize that it has its limitations in the digital age.

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:51.440
[Guest]: And in that sense, I kind of fell into history almost accidentally, because I was working on my

00:05:51.440 --> 00:06:00.640
[Guest]: master's thesis in Montreal at the moment. This is around 2012-2013. And what happens in a fine art

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:06.560
[Guest]: program is that you can essentially work on any subject you want for your research, as long as you

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:11.920
[Guest]: produce a body of work, physical work that can be hung in a gallery, and that you will defend.

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:19.280
[Guest]: So like most people defend papers during their thesis, people like me would defend a body of artwork.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:25.040
[Guest]: And for this, I don't know how I got really interested. Well, I know how I got really

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:30.160
[Guest]: interested in the partition of India. I was in my grad program for two years, and the third year was

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:36.560
[Guest]: supposed to be the thesis year. And I remember taking a sabbatical year off, because I just

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:41.360
[Guest]: didn't have any ideas for my thesis. And I think the thing with any creative practice is that the

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:46.640
[Guest]: more you push it, the more it's visible that you've pushed it. And it doesn't seem natural.

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:52.080
[Guest]: It doesn't seem like it's coming from within. So I took a gap year. I moved home, back to India

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:58.720
[Guest]: from Canada. And I said, okay, if the idea needs to come, it's going to come naturally. And I remember

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:05.600
[Guest]: it was 2013, October. And I have a friend, my aunt Austin Sufi, who's more popularly known as the

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:12.240
[Guest]: Delhiwala. And he and I went to my grandfather's house in North Delhi, because my aunt was writing

00:07:12.240 --> 00:07:18.480
[Guest]: a story about old houses in the city at that time. And he asked us questions, of course, about the

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:24.880
[Guest]: house that my grandfather lived in, which was built in the 50s. And I, that day, started seeing the

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:31.360
[Guest]: house through a very different lens. Added to this fact was my grandfather's elder brother, who

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:36.560
[Guest]: brought up all these old objects. And a lot of those objects had been carried from across the

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:42.320
[Guest]: border before partition. And two objects specifically that had been carried by his parents to Delhi,

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:47.840
[Guest]: they came from Lahore to Amritsar, and finally to Delhi. And these were very, very mundane

00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:54.560
[Guest]: home-based objects, a ghara, in which lassi is made, a metal vessel, and a ghaz, a yardstick,

00:07:55.440 --> 00:08:01.600
[Guest]: which was used in the clothing store to measure fabric. It's called a ghaz. And I think that when

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:07.920
[Guest]: my grandfather's brother started talking about these two objects, it was so visceral, because he

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:14.240
[Guest]: was transported back to his childhood in Lahore. And it was not just the fact that he was transported

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:20.160
[Guest]: to the past, which happens quite commonly with, you know, aged artifacts, but also the fact that

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:26.560
[Guest]: he was transported across this really impenetrable border, almost seamlessly in front of me. And I

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:32.240
[Guest]: don't think anyone else noticed that happening, but I became obsessed with the idea that the object

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:37.360
[Guest]: can transport us somewhere. And of course, you know, objects do this, old objects, when we hold

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:44.080
[Guest]: them, they remind us of other times, they remind us of other people. But that idea of being transported

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:50.880
[Guest]: across a border by an object was so powerful for me. And I think in that moment, I realized that I

00:08:50.880 --> 00:08:58.320
[Guest]: found my MFA thesis idea. So I spent the next year, I would say traveling around India, interviewing

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:04.080
[Guest]: people about objects. And I'm sure we'll go more into the interview process later. So I'm just

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:10.000
[Guest]: going to tell you a very brief overview. And when I went back to Canada, after my one year

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:16.880
[Guest]: sabbatical was when I started really working on using historical images, which is a very

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:24.080
[Guest]: important thing that I'm working on, using historical information to create artwork that I would

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:27.680
[Guest]: finally showcase in a gallery and defend at some point.

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:33.280
[Amit Varma]: Right. So, you know, my sort of interface with this project is, of course, a book, you know, when it

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:38.080
[Amit Varma]: originated, were you thinking of it as sort of artwork? Were you thinking of it as, you know,

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:42.960
[Amit Varma]: it'll come together as a book? Were you merely simply at that point, not thinking of form so

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:48.400
[Amit Varma]: much, but just fascinated by the process of, you know, excavating memory through talking about

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:53.280
[Amit Varma]: things as it were, and then letting that lead where it will? What was your thought process that

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:56.240
[Amit Varma]: led you through this entire project?

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:01.920
[Guest]: I don't think I ever thought of it as a book at the beginning. And to be honest, I don't think

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:11.920
[Guest]: I thought of it as a book until 2016, as late as 2016. And I have been raised in a family that

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:17.920
[Guest]: owns a bookshop. So books are very intrinsic to me. And despite that, I never did anything in it.

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:22.640
[Guest]: That it was always about the visual for me, because I was interested in art, I was good at art.

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:27.760
[Guest]: And then I went to college for art as well. So I think when I started on the idea, it was very

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:34.560
[Guest]: much about the physicality of the object, the emotions attached to the object. How can I portray

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:40.880
[Guest]: something in a photograph that transports someone to that moment? Right. But what I was also doing,

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:45.520
[Guest]: and for this, I guess I have great hindsight, you know, I have great foresight, is that I was

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:51.920
[Guest]: interviewing people about the object. So everything that would essentially be included in an oral

00:10:51.920 --> 00:10:57.040
[Guest]: history interview was happening anyway, because I was curious about the object, which meant that

00:10:57.040 --> 00:11:01.680
[Guest]: when eventually I did realize that I wanted to make this into a book, I had a lot of subject

00:11:01.680 --> 00:11:07.600
[Guest]: matter ready available for me. But at the beginning, it was really just about the thesis and

00:11:07.600 --> 00:11:12.480
[Guest]: making something visual and making something. I think also because I was I was living in Canada,

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:17.920
[Guest]: and people over there really did not know enough about South Asian history. So it also became a

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:25.040
[Guest]: way to make people more aware of diverse histories. But the book was never really on the cards at the

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:31.440
[Amit Varma]: beginning. And how does the expected audience of a work play a part in shaping the work itself?

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:36.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, I've often found that, you know, a decade ago, I used to write for foreign papers,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
[Amit Varma]: like the Wall Street Journal, The Guardian, and so on. And I eventually stopped because I hated it,

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.800
[Amit Varma]: because I found that a lot of shared knowledge that one takes for granted when one writes for

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:49.440
[Amit Varma]: an Indian audience, you know, you can't take that for granted. And you have to dump everything down.

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:53.840
[Amit Varma]: And you have to, you know, explain even the simplest thing. And the thing is that for an

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:58.640
[Amit Varma]: Indian reader of your book, knowing what I know about the partition, even my dad, you know,

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:02.320
[Amit Varma]: went from Lahore to Calcutta, though, that was not at the partition, but well before.

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:06.720
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, there's a certain shared knowledge and empathy that you can take for granted,

00:12:06.720 --> 00:12:11.840
[Amit Varma]: which is not so with the foreign reader, does that then sort of shape the art that you're

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:18.160
[Amit Varma]: producing that a certain amount of the space goes into explanatory stuff, just giving the background,

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:22.400
[Amit Varma]: whereas, you know, for a different audience, perhaps you'd have less of that and

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:26.800
[Amit Varma]: more of just, you know, evoking the time and the emotions and all of that.

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:34.480
[Guest]: Well, I mean, I think there's a two part answer to that. The first is that visual art can transcend

00:12:34.480 --> 00:12:40.560
[Guest]: language, which means that it can transcend specific histories, right? When you're looking

00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:46.480
[Guest]: at a painting or a photograph, or even a film, you may not have to be born in that specific

00:12:46.480 --> 00:12:51.440
[Guest]: geographic area to feel something that it's trying to make you feel. So that's, that's one

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:57.280
[Guest]: of the, it's one of the positive aspects about art. And obviously art has many positive aspects,

00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:04.880
[Guest]: but I didn't really feel like the images had to be explained. What I felt was that the history

00:13:04.880 --> 00:13:11.520
[Guest]: behind the images had to be explained, which is actually what also started getting me towards

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:18.080
[Guest]: the book, that there was so much that an image could not give to someone that words had to be

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:24.640
[Guest]: put. But the other thing, the second part about that answer is, is a sense of emotion. What you're

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:30.560
[Guest]: trying to do is not to put together a conventional history of partition, but a human history of

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:38.000
[Guest]: partition. And I think when it comes to feelings of migration, displacement, loss, particularly

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.280
[Guest]: in the country where I was living, Canada, which is largely for my immigrants, I think there was

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:50.160
[Guest]: a lot of resonance. And the larger teams had a lot of resonance, the specificity may have been lost,

00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:56.800
[Guest]: but the larger themes about leaving a place, either by choice or by force, could be felt by

00:13:56.800 --> 00:14:01.760
[Amit Varma]: many people. How did you sort of then begin, like to speak about the interviewing itself, and

00:14:01.760 --> 00:14:06.400
[Amit Varma]: we briefly spoke about it before we started recording, where you reminded me that you're

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:10.720
[Amit Varma]: a professional interviewer, and therefore out of great curiosity and hoping that I can learn

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:15.200
[Amit Varma]: something from this, how did you approach that process? Because I of course, you know, I sort of

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:20.000
[Amit Varma]: have willing participants, when I talk to people on my show, they know what I'm doing. There's that

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.800
[Amit Varma]: common ground, it's not that difficult, though one does have, you know, little things one does to

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:28.880
[Amit Varma]: make them comfortable, and so on. But in your case, you're speaking to people who are literally

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:34.400
[Amit Varma]: decades older than you. And what is even harder is that many of the things you want them to talk

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:39.280
[Amit Varma]: about, they could include things that they've suppressed for years and years. So your task is

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:44.720
[Amit Varma]: first to make them comfortable, and then to make them open up and to make them take you seriously.

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:50.640
[Amit Varma]: So what was that process of learning how to have these conversations? And what tips can you share

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:56.080
[Guest]: for other would-be conversationalists? I think learning is the key word here, because I'm still

00:14:56.080 --> 00:15:01.600
[Guest]: very much learning how to do it. And I think like, working with people is, you know, gives you a

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:08.720
[Guest]: sense of great humility, because you're constantly learning. I started this work when I was 23 years

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:17.520
[Guest]: old, which meant 2013. 23 is a very young age to do anything of this serious nature. And at the

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:24.240
[Guest]: beginning, as you would expect, I had a lot of issues. Because I don't know why at that point,

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:29.440
[Guest]: I thought it would be a great idea not to do any secondary research at the beginning. So to really

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:36.960
[Guest]: go in straight, fresh, fill my head with personal knowledge about people, and then later do my

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:40.800
[Guest]: secondary research, which in hindsight was not a great idea, because I didn't really know what I

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:46.640
[Guest]: was getting into. But I have since thought about the interview process a lot. And I can maybe

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:55.040
[Guest]: start at the beginning as to what I felt at the beginning. So in those first few interviews in

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:59.680
[Guest]: 2013, I found it very difficult to start asking questions, because the thing is,

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:04.960
[Guest]: you're right, you're not asking about how was your day, tell me about your kitty party.

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:11.360
[Guest]: Let's talk about this the bola thing you played. No, it's actually tell me when you left your home

00:16:11.360 --> 00:16:18.320
[Guest]: and tell me how it felt. And tell me whether you were scared. What did you do? And these are really

00:16:19.360 --> 00:16:26.640
[Guest]: how to start saying these things. How do you reach common ground. And so I have something which I

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:34.080
[Guest]: unofficially called the plateau method, which is, if you want someone to reach here, up here,

00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:39.840
[Guest]: then you have to make it your responsibility to also reach here, which means that if someone would

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:46.400
[Guest]: be saying something of great vulnerability, I'm not saying that you have to say equally the same

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:51.280
[Guest]: amount of vulnerable things, but you have to give yourself to the person as well, which means

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:58.000
[Guest]: you have to be a couple of things, honest, sincere, and genuinely interested in what they're saying.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:04.400
[Guest]: I think the largest issue with being a millennial is that I had to learn how to listen to people,

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:11.440
[Guest]: right, which is a really underrated, underrated habit, listening. And I think when you're an older

00:17:11.440 --> 00:17:16.400
[Guest]: auto historian, and you're working with older people, that is key to listen to them, because

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:19.840
[Guest]: you can go in with a structured interview, which by the way, is something I never do.

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:24.560
[Guest]: And you can ask all the questions and they can answer all the questions, but you still may not

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:29.600
[Guest]: get anything of significance from them. The point is to listen to what they're saying and ask follow

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:34.720
[Guest]: up questions based on what they have said. And these could be really mundane questions, like

00:17:34.720 --> 00:17:40.160
[Guest]: tell me how you made your hair. Did you wear a braid? Or did you wear a ponytail when you were

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:46.480
[Guest]: young? Or tell me what you wore? Because I realized very, very early on that to talk about partition

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:51.840
[Guest]: is very difficult still, which means that there is something so extraordinary about the 1947

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:56.960
[Guest]: partition that we haven't been able to let go of its heaviness. And part of that is because

00:17:56.960 --> 00:18:02.800
[Guest]: we haven't talked about its heaviness. So if something remains suppressed for years, then

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:07.280
[Guest]: it's almost as if every conversation is starting at the beginning of unravelling something about,

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:16.640
[Guest]: right. And so, in that sense, because my study was about objects, it made it a little bit easier,

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:23.440
[Guest]: actually, because I could say, okay, tell me about this pen. Why did you carry this pen? How did you

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:28.000
[Guest]: carry this pen? Oh, your father gave you this pen, okay, it was very expensive at the time.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:33.360
[Guest]: And then how did you know that you had to carry things? How did you learn about partition? You

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:38.560
[Guest]: heard it on the radio? Okay, what radio did you listen to? What newspaper did you get in your home?

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:45.840
[Guest]: So what I was trying to do was not only archive memory about partition, because that's a limited

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:52.720
[Guest]: event. What I was trying to do is to archive the social ethnography of life before partition in an

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:57.840
[Guest]: undivided India and how it was fractured because of partition. For that, we need to furnish people's

00:18:57.840 --> 00:19:02.880
[Guest]: lives with details. And I think that we have this great misconception that partition happened

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:11.520
[Guest]: in August 1947. And that's the month of mayhem. And that's it. But in fact, it started much before

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:17.040
[Guest]: that. And it took many months, even years to normalize. Some would argue that the repercussions

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:22.800
[Guest]: still haven't normalized per se, even now. But I think that in asking questions only about the

00:19:22.800 --> 00:19:28.800
[Guest]: violence or the trauma or migration of displacement, you already limit your interview to that lens.

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:38.320
[Guest]: And there is a great injustice in that because then you only paint the event of partition as an

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:46.000
[Guest]: event of trauma. Whereas there were moments of great sacrifice and friendship and camaraderie

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:51.760
[Guest]: that came from that event that were born because of the circumstances of partition and you lose

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:58.320
[Guest]: out on the opportunity with the cultures. So one of the things that I did was to be completely

00:19:58.320 --> 00:20:05.440
[Guest]: open in my interviewing process, which leads you to a lot of tangential stories, particularly with

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:11.200
[Guest]: old people, because they talk a lot because someone is listening. And that's really what

00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:19.040
[Guest]: they want for someone to listen. So we would be talking about a bomb blast at the time,

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:23.360
[Guest]: then we would suddenly go to the school they went to. Then from there, we would go to the stones

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:28.160
[Guest]: they would collect as a child and a paper book they made. And it was just really all over the

00:20:28.160 --> 00:20:34.400
[Guest]: place, which also tells you that memory is not chronological and it does not work in a linear

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:40.400
[Guest]: fashion. And I think that, if anything, the interview process continues to be a very humbling

00:20:40.400 --> 00:20:47.920
[Guest]: process for me, because it just makes you realize how small you are in the larger aspect of

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:54.000
[Amit Varma]: lives or national history. And the focus on objects, you know, it struck me while

00:20:54.800 --> 00:20:59.280
[Amit Varma]: reading your book and reading you speak about it elsewhere that, you know, there are two ways in

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:03.440
[Amit Varma]: which the focus on objects can really work. And one is, of course, it's a catalyst, it can

00:21:03.440 --> 00:21:07.200
[Amit Varma]: just get them to open up when you say where did this pen come from, and they start talking about

00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:12.640
[Amit Varma]: that and other memories flow. But also, objects can intrinsically be meaningful. Like I was very

00:21:12.640 --> 00:21:17.760
[Amit Varma]: moved by the story that you told near the start of the book of your paternal grandmother, who

00:21:17.760 --> 00:21:22.160
[Amit Varma]: shows you her coin collection, right? And at that moment, it's just a mundane collection of old

00:21:22.160 --> 00:21:28.720
[Amit Varma]: coins. But then she talks about how her parents lived in this joint family thing, and her dad

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:33.600
[Amit Varma]: died. And the rest of the family cut them all out, even though they were staying there. And her mom

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:38.320
[Amit Varma]: didn't know how to cope and they didn't have any money. And one day, her mom sends her out to all

00:21:38.320 --> 00:21:42.800
[Amit Varma]: the other relatives to, you know, get some money and none of them gives anything. And what is she

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:47.680
[Amit Varma]: asking for? She's asking for five rupees. And when she says that she picks up five of those

00:21:47.680 --> 00:21:52.320
[Amit Varma]: one rupee coins, you know, there are so many other stories like this, like the lady who carries a

00:21:52.320 --> 00:21:56.720
[Amit Varma]: sword and then you realize that that sword has a greater significance and just being the one item

00:21:56.720 --> 00:22:01.520
[Amit Varma]: they carried with them, that when they were sort of running away through those jungles or whatever

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:05.680
[Amit Varma]: and getting away, she actually gave birth to her kid and that sword was used to cut the umbilical

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:12.000
[Amit Varma]: cord. So that's, you know, so sort of significant. There's also the you know, the ghara of lassi,

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:16.320
[Amit Varma]: which you spoke about, where and you know, when you were describing that bit of ghara in which

00:22:16.320 --> 00:22:21.840
[Amit Varma]: lassi was still made every day. And it struck me that it's almost like a series of cinematic

00:22:21.840 --> 00:22:26.880
[Amit Varma]: shots where you're zooming out where first you have an inanimate object, which is a ghara and

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:31.680
[Amit Varma]: then you zoom out to the making of lassi and then you zoom out to the people making it and all the

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:35.920
[Amit Varma]: history and everything that has happened. Were these objects intrinsically valuable to these

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:42.720
[Amit Varma]: people already? Or did they gain value as they sort of, you know, as these memories roll through

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:50.160
[Guest]: them? I think both depending on the object. So say you carried something that was

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:57.360
[Guest]: obviously valuable, and by that I mean monetarily valuable. Jewelry, piece of silver, an heirloom.

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:04.560
[Guest]: Then these objects were kept in beautiful pristine condition and brought out and sort of

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:11.040
[Guest]: celebrated, okay, look, we brought this from there. Look, I can put it on right now. It's

00:23:11.040 --> 00:23:15.680
[Guest]: almost like a celebration of things, you know, and this is particularly the case with jewelry.

00:23:15.680 --> 00:23:22.800
[Guest]: But say you brought something so mundane like a ghaz, a yardstick, and you didn't

00:23:22.800 --> 00:23:28.480
[Guest]: use it, you weren't a cloth seller anymore in India, then what happened to the ghaz? It would

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:32.720
[Guest]: be sitting in a corner of your house and you would almost forget about it. That was the case with the

00:23:32.720 --> 00:23:40.160
[Guest]: sword mentioned. Ajit Paul Kapoor runs through the jungles of Kashmir state and arrives in Jammu,

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:47.040
[Guest]: having given birth on the third day of her flight, and her husband uses the sword to cut her umbilical

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:53.280
[Guest]: cord. So in that sense, the sword literally saves her life. And yet the sword had been relegated to

00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:59.680
[Guest]: a dusty corner of the house. Now, maybe that's because she didn't want to remember the trauma

00:23:59.680 --> 00:24:06.960
[Guest]: attached to that flight and thereby attached to that sword as well. But this should be an example

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:13.680
[Guest]: of how objects can fall from grace and how they are not remembered. But generally I found if things

00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:21.040
[Guest]: were of extreme mundane nature, books, shawls, pens, this pocket knife that my grandmother carried,

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:26.720
[Guest]: for example, then you would have to infuse importance into it, which also tells you about

00:24:27.760 --> 00:24:34.000
[Guest]: what is valuable for people in the subcontinent. Right? If something is obviously sparkly and

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:40.240
[Guest]: glittery and has money attached to it, then you will take care of it. But if something is really

00:24:40.240 --> 00:24:45.360
[Guest]: mundane, it is not celebrated for its virtuosity or the fact that it has survived or the fact that

00:24:45.360 --> 00:24:52.000
[Guest]: it has seen so many important journeys. It is almost forgotten. So in a sense, if we were

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:57.360
[Guest]: talking about a shawl, for example, and I would say, Oh, how beautiful. And I would go on and I

00:24:57.360 --> 00:25:02.400
[Guest]: would talk about it. They may not have cared about it at the beginning of our conversation.

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:05.680
[Guest]: But if by chance at the end of our two or three hour conversation, I would say,

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:10.720
[Guest]: can I borrow the shawl for my research? I'll return it. They would say, no, no, no. It's mine.

00:25:10.720 --> 00:25:16.160
[Guest]: It's my mother's. It's my father's. So I think that the jump or the shift from

00:25:17.680 --> 00:25:23.360
[Guest]: nonchalance towards a particular object, particularly mundane things to proprietorship

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:31.200
[Guest]: was so, um, it was almost like so cliche towards the end, because I knew that it would happen.

00:25:31.200 --> 00:25:37.760
[Guest]: Right. Um, in that sense, I think that objects teach you a lot of things as well, right? They

00:25:37.760 --> 00:25:44.400
[Guest]: teach you, as you said, how to be catalysts for certain things. And I think that this was a method

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:53.920
[Guest]: of storytelling I discovered while on the field. So because I wasn't trained in, in history or

00:25:53.920 --> 00:25:59.920
[Guest]: English or any form of sociology, anthropology or ethnography, a lot of this had to be learned

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:04.640
[Guest]: on the field. And I should say that there are dedicated programs in colleges and universities

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:10.320
[Guest]: now that teach that. But because you have to learn everything on the field, a couple of things

00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:16.080
[Guest]: happen. A, things are a lot harder for you, right? And you have to problem solve literally all the

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:22.720
[Guest]: time. But the second thing that happens is that you develop really creative ways to do things.

00:26:22.720 --> 00:26:26.640
[Guest]: And these are things that people learn about in schools and stuff. And here you are, because you,

00:26:26.640 --> 00:26:32.640
[Guest]: you've derived it from necessity almost. So in that sense, I think a lot of my methodology is

00:26:32.640 --> 00:26:41.040
[Guest]: really grounded into the discovery of specific history. I am not interested in the extraneous

00:26:41.040 --> 00:26:46.880
[Guest]: details at all. I am not interested in the larger scope of landscape. The person, no,

00:26:46.880 --> 00:26:53.680
[Guest]: I'm interested in the nuanced, highly detailed, personal perspective of the person, because

00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:59.040
[Guest]: the history of partition has long been relegated to numbers and figures and facts and date.

00:26:59.760 --> 00:27:05.680
[Guest]: And I did not understand how my grandparents, all four of whom had migrated from what became

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:10.800
[Guest]: Pakistan to India had become numbers. I just didn't get that. So that meant that for every

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:15.440
[Guest]: number, there was a person's story. And I was interested in that specific story.

00:27:15.440 --> 00:27:22.880
[Guest]: So I built methodology around trying to record the specificities of people's lives.

00:27:22.880 --> 00:27:27.520
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the sort of continuous strands that comes up through your book is that many of

00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:31.360
[Amit Varma]: these people sharing these memories, even if they're sort of insiders, even if they're part

00:27:31.360 --> 00:27:36.480
[Amit Varma]: of the establishment at the time, to them partition is an abstract concept before it happens.

00:27:36.480 --> 00:27:40.720
[Amit Varma]: And then it becomes concrete. And it seems to me that a lot of what this book does is also make

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:46.480
[Amit Varma]: the abstract concrete that very often when you talk of history, dates, events, this happened,

00:27:46.480 --> 00:27:50.960
[Amit Varma]: that happened, it's all abstract, it's just stuff on the page. And what you've done is you've,

00:27:50.960 --> 00:27:56.640
[Amit Varma]: of course, told all of these stories and made it kind of come to life and become so evocative for

00:27:57.280 --> 00:28:02.400
[Amit Varma]: all of us. You know, and the interesting thing is that so many of them at the time had no idea

00:28:02.400 --> 00:28:07.680
[Amit Varma]: what the consequences of these abstract things would be until their lives are completely overturned.

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:12.320
[Amit Varma]: As an interviewer did some of this sort of take you by surprise. And, you know, when you listen

00:28:12.320 --> 00:28:16.960
[Amit Varma]: to all these stories, these people reliving memories that they might have suppressed for so

00:28:16.960 --> 00:28:22.240
[Amit Varma]: long. And of course, you said in terms of that whole plat you method, which, you know, I shall

00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:27.920
[Amit Varma]: have to process and perhaps try out myself, you know, it must be so emotionally charged for you

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:32.480
[Amit Varma]: as well to listen to these stories. And particularly when some of these people are your

00:28:32.480 --> 00:28:38.080
[Amit Varma]: relative, so to say, and you've also descended from four people affected by partition, all your

00:28:38.080 --> 00:28:44.480
[Guest]: grandparents. I think that interviewing your family is the hardest, because you don't know

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:51.760
[Guest]: what you may find. And you don't know how that may affect the day to day after that. Right.

00:28:51.760 --> 00:28:55.360
[Guest]: And I'm not just talking about like skeletons in the closet sort of things you may find,

00:28:55.360 --> 00:29:00.800
[Guest]: but just generally also like, just discovering the sacrifices and difficulties that they had

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:06.640
[Guest]: to go through really changes your perception of a person. Right. So that's one. The second thing is

00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:11.920
[Guest]: being emotionally involved in an interview. I don't know how to explain this without

00:29:11.920 --> 00:29:18.400
[Guest]: sounding like a very crass person. But I'm not a very emotional person. And I'm very good at

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:24.320
[Guest]: keeping, you know, work and personal life very separate. And I think that this is one of the

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:28.400
[Guest]: reasons that people are often disappointed when they meet me, because they often expect me to be

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:34.240
[Guest]: like a very compassionate person, always wanting to hear their stories. But in fact, it gets a lot,

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:39.840
[Guest]: to be honest, if you're listening to stories all the time, it gets quite mentally taxing.

00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:48.960
[Guest]: So when I am on an interview, my main focus is to be able to record as much information

00:29:48.960 --> 00:29:53.120
[Guest]: as possible. Because I have a rule with people, I don't see them more than once.

00:29:53.120 --> 00:29:58.400
[Guest]: So the interview happens on one day. And it may be for two hours, or it may be for four hours,

00:29:58.400 --> 00:30:03.760
[Guest]: it may have 10 breaks in the middle, or it may have no breaks. But I try my best not to go back

00:30:03.760 --> 00:30:09.600
[Guest]: to the person because I find that if you go back the second and third time, then they know exactly

00:30:09.600 --> 00:30:15.600
[Guest]: what you want to hear and how you want to hear it. So and then they would have had a chance to

00:30:16.560 --> 00:30:21.440
[Guest]: process and reason with their history in some way. Whereas when you're talking to them for

00:30:21.440 --> 00:30:27.680
[Guest]: the first time, if they are rediscovering something, then you are discovering it along

00:30:27.680 --> 00:30:34.160
[Guest]: with them. So the process is very raw. But I think that you have to be very careful not to

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:39.120
[Guest]: entangle yourself in that conversation, because you're still having to make sense of it and ask

00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:47.040
[Guest]: the questions. It's very easy to get swayed into the trauma and violence of what people saw and

00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:53.600
[Guest]: lose yourself in it. And this particular thing happens to me only when I'm listening to the

00:30:53.600 --> 00:30:59.200
[Guest]: interview again to transcribe it. When I'm in that moment, all I want to ask is a follow up

00:30:59.200 --> 00:31:05.920
[Guest]: question. I want to ask how they feel. I want to ask what it was like. And often the responses

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:12.880
[Guest]: take people by surprise as well. Either because they are being asked so directly, or the fact

00:31:12.880 --> 00:31:19.840
[Guest]: that they are being asked at all. Because for much of this generation's life, it's not that

00:31:19.840 --> 00:31:24.560
[Guest]: they just didn't talk about it. It's also the fact that they were never asked about it. So

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:30.960
[Guest]: when I'm there, I'm trying to get as much information as I can. Of course, things are

00:31:30.960 --> 00:31:38.000
[Guest]: emotional. Of course, you feel it. Of course, some of the things you hear are horribly inhuman.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:42.640
[Guest]: So you can't help but feel moved by them. But you always have to remember that this story is not

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:49.040
[Guest]: your story, even though it may be unearthed because of you. But when you're transcribing,

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:54.880
[Guest]: and you're really focusing on the words people are using. For example, a thing that always gets

00:31:54.880 --> 00:32:01.120
[Guest]: to me a lot is that people of that generation say something of that time of partition, they

00:32:01.120 --> 00:32:06.880
[Guest]: will always say, humne body dispose kar di, we had to dispose of the body. And that word dispose,

00:32:06.880 --> 00:32:14.400
[Guest]: it really gets to me always, because it's such a like, I would use it for, for trash. Right?

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:19.680
[Guest]: I would use it, you know, I'm disposing of this, I don't need it anymore. But they often use that

00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:25.200
[Guest]: word to describe people that had died, and they had to either cremate them or bury them at the

00:32:25.200 --> 00:32:31.920
[Guest]: time. So I think that what I'm looking out for, and I'm concentrating on is the vocabulary when

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:38.560
[Guest]: I'm transcribing, and that really gets to me. But again, I think that you need to make a certain

00:32:38.560 --> 00:32:43.200
[Guest]: amount of distance from the interview. And it happens already, because you're so much younger,

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:49.680
[Guest]: and they're so much older. And the distance is so, so large, so vast, not in terms of generation,

00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:54.640
[Guest]: but also in terms of time and the fact that you have social media to help you understand other

00:32:54.640 --> 00:33:00.000
[Guest]: things and connect with other people that you feel the same thing. What was the original question?

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:04.800
[Amit Varma]: Oh, you know, I mean, I'm delighted that even I have sort of lost track of the original question,

00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:10.400
[Amit Varma]: but I think you answered it. And then we went on a very amethyst digression, if I might say that,

00:33:10.400 --> 00:33:15.680
[Amit Varma]: which is most welcome. So these are the tangents I'm talking about, like, you just get very used to

00:33:15.680 --> 00:33:21.360
[Guest]: it, you know, because the thing is, I'm still trying to make sense of the craft of oral history.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:27.680
[Guest]: I think that it's not given as much importance as it should be, particularly in the context of

00:33:27.680 --> 00:33:34.480
[Guest]: the subcontinent. It's, you know, history from beneath, or it's only people's history. And I

00:33:34.480 --> 00:33:39.520
[Guest]: think the biggest question I get sometimes with it that often aggravates me is, how can you trust

00:33:39.520 --> 00:33:48.720
[Guest]: it? How can you trust memory? And how can you not? How can you not? Like, even if someone is making

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:55.040
[Guest]: something up, even if someone has adopted a collective history to make it their personal

00:33:55.040 --> 00:33:59.920
[Guest]: history at the time, which is very common with partitions. So because everyone was seeing dead

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:05.200
[Guest]: bodies, someone who may not have seen a dead body, but only heard about it may have adopted that

00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:11.440
[Guest]: story as their own. But even if that is the case, how can you not listen to it and hold it as a

00:34:11.440 --> 00:34:17.040
[Guest]: valid source? Because at some point, oral history becomes a part of the subcontinent. And that's

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:21.680
[Guest]: because at some point, oral history becomes the only way we can actually populate these events

00:34:21.680 --> 00:34:28.720
[Guest]: with actual details. Conventional history has not been able to do that, which is why we study

00:34:28.720 --> 00:34:34.000
[Guest]: partition in school and not understand it to be an event that belongs to us, but an event that is so

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:39.280
[Guest]: far back in the pages of history that it cannot possibly have an effect on the present, which,

00:34:39.280 --> 00:34:43.680
[Guest]: as we've seen in recent years, is obviously not the case. Partition is still trickling

00:34:43.680 --> 00:34:49.520
[Guest]: down to generations. So I think that, I don't know, over these last, and again, going off on

00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:55.200
[Guest]: a really weird tangent here, that I have learned how to be a champion for oral history, for people's

00:34:55.200 --> 00:35:00.080
[Guest]: history, which I think more and more people are now. So a two part question, really, actually,

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:03.680
[Amit Varma]: there are a lot of questions which emerge from what you just said, which is why I keep a notebook

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:08.960
[Amit Varma]: with me. But a two part question to begin with, which is that, you know, one you pointed out

00:35:08.960 --> 00:35:12.560
[Amit Varma]: during the book, and this is something that we all know that a lot of people from that generation

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:17.440
[Amit Varma]: who went through partition have never told these stories. And perhaps the first time they were

00:35:17.440 --> 00:35:22.080
[Amit Varma]: talking about it was talking about it to you, even the family didn't really know these things.

00:35:22.720 --> 00:35:26.480
[Amit Varma]: So number one, you know, why do you think so many of those people suppress these stories?

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And the second part of that is that I guess, one reason no one would have asked them about

00:35:30.880 --> 00:35:35.040
[Amit Varma]: these stories is that they would have, it would have felt impolite that you don't want to go to

00:35:35.040 --> 00:35:39.200
[Amit Varma]: a place where somebody else doesn't want to go, which of course, is part of your work you had to

00:35:39.200 --> 00:35:44.560
[Amit Varma]: do. So did you, did you feel like an intruder? And did you sometimes feel guilty for, you know,

00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:50.320
[Guest]: dredging up all this pain and trauma from the past? Yes, yes, sometimes, not always, though,

00:35:50.320 --> 00:35:56.960
[Guest]: because that's what you're there for. But I remember, you know, distinctly remember this

00:35:56.960 --> 00:36:00.800
[Guest]: interview that actually happened after the book was published. So I haven't, I haven't actually

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:09.440
[Guest]: written about it anywhere. But I remember interviewing this couple in Gurgaon. And the

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:19.680
[Guest]: woman had come from erstwhile J&K state. And she had traveled to Jammu with her cute, with this

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:24.240
[Guest]: huge family. And so the details that came out of that interview, they left on Karva Chauth day.

00:36:24.960 --> 00:36:30.240
[Guest]: And how she knows that is because it was a full moon. It was a full moon. And she knows everyone

00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:34.000
[Guest]: was fasting, all the women were fasting. So she was particular to tell me that we left on Karva

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:42.320
[Guest]: Chauth day. And they left with a really big group of people. And they left in such a hurry that they

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:47.600
[Guest]: actually left behind her sister. She was sleeping in the house, and they just left her behind. And

00:36:47.600 --> 00:36:55.520
[Guest]: she was an older sister for her. So all these people are migrating to India at the time. And,

00:36:55.520 --> 00:37:02.240
[Guest]: you know, in, there was not a lot of migration that happened in August 47 in J&K. The migration

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:08.960
[Guest]: only started in October, November with attacks from what were called Kabalis at that time. Now

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:14.960
[Guest]: who is a Kabali? What is a Kabali? It's difficult to say. But they call it Kabali. So I will call

00:37:14.960 --> 00:37:21.600
[Guest]: it Kabali as well. And so she is saying that we are running and people are running after us. And

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:28.320
[Guest]: there's a lot of confusion. And we end up in this little house or small fort like thing. And we are

00:37:28.320 --> 00:37:36.480
[Guest]: all taking shelter there. And then my aunt starts passing out what is called Ram Nam Ki Goli,

00:37:36.480 --> 00:37:42.720
[Guest]: which is cyanide pills. And they're passing that they're breaking and she gets a small piece and

00:37:42.720 --> 00:37:49.360
[Guest]: everyone is ingesting them so that they don't have to meet a worst fate. If you have to die,

00:37:49.360 --> 00:37:56.080
[Guest]: die at your own hands, then something worse. So she puts it in her mouth. She's very young at the

00:37:56.080 --> 00:38:00.240
[Guest]: time. I don't think she was older than four or five. She puts it in her mouth and she finds it

00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:06.960
[Guest]: very bitter. So she spits it out. In that sense, she saves her life. And from the large party that

00:38:06.960 --> 00:38:13.200
[Guest]: had left, I think four people remain. And they come to India, I believe they come to Delhi.

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:18.320
[Guest]: And the sister is still missing. And they just, they figure when they reach here, they just

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:24.240
[Guest]: know when they reach here, she's been left behind and not much can be done. Ultimately, she's picked

00:38:24.240 --> 00:38:31.840
[Guest]: up by a Muslim man there, taken to his house. He takes care of her as his child. He then takes her

00:38:31.840 --> 00:38:37.360
[Guest]: after a couple of years to a camp, where she realizes that someone from the family has been

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:45.360
[Guest]: looking for her all this time and they are reunited. And now, this narrating this incident

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:52.080
[Guest]: is causing this woman a lot of pain, right? Because, but it's not a, I can't explain it because

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:58.880
[Guest]: she was so young at the time, the pain is also very childlike. So the ways in which she describes

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:05.440
[Guest]: it is, when I saw my sister, I didn't recognize that she was my sister. But I remember what she

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:11.200
[Guest]: was wearing. She was wearing a dress. And she was very, very thin. And she was walking down the

00:39:11.200 --> 00:39:15.680
[Guest]: stairs. And I saw her for the first time. And I had to be reintroduced to my sister.

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:21.760
[Guest]: She tells me that she lost almost all her family on that journey. And then she says,

00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:29.120
[Guest]: I don't blame Muslims for it. In fact, I don't blame anyone for it.

00:39:31.520 --> 00:39:35.680
[Guest]: Those were the times. And then she leaves the room and she goes to make a cup of tea. Now,

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:40.000
[Guest]: I don't know whether she left the room because she was overwhelmed or she left the room simply

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.240
[Guest]: because she had to make a cup of tea for us. But her husband who's been sitting in on this

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:50.240
[Guest]: conversation, he turns to me and says, come help me take out the clothes from outside.

00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:58.800
[Guest]: And I walk with him. And while we're walking, he says, why are you asking these questions?

00:39:59.920 --> 00:40:01.840
[Guest]: Don't you see the pain that you're causing?

00:40:01.840 --> 00:40:09.200
[Guest]: And it's just like, how do you respond to that? You know, I didn't know what to say. I was just,

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:15.360
[Guest]: on one hand, this is your work. Because if you don't do it, then no one will know.

00:40:15.360 --> 00:40:20.560
[Guest]: And no one will know. That means people will repeat this again and again. So on one level,

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:25.680
[Guest]: you're recording for public knowledge, to make sure something like this never happens again.

00:40:25.680 --> 00:40:31.360
[Guest]: On the other hand, saying this may be causing someone pain, subliminal pain also, that they

00:40:31.360 --> 00:40:36.800
[Guest]: may not be telling you. And who knows what kind of conversations emerge after you leave that house.

00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:45.040
[Guest]: So what did I do in that moment? So the gentleman takes off all the clothes that are drying outside,

00:40:45.040 --> 00:40:52.400
[Guest]: he takes them inside. And then the clothes string is like very prickly. So he takes it off and

00:40:52.400 --> 00:40:59.600
[Guest]: the clothes string is like very prickly, that kind of plastic jute. I didn't know what else to do.

00:40:59.600 --> 00:41:06.080
[Guest]: So I just held on to it really tight until I felt some physical pain. And then I let it go.

00:41:06.720 --> 00:41:13.680
[Guest]: And I don't know why I did that. But I just felt really sad because of what he said. But he was

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:19.520
[Guest]: right. He was right, you know. And you do feel like you're causing people pain. Of course, not

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:26.400
[Guest]: everyone, not everyone. But then sometimes when stories are this traumatic, I don't know, I want

00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:33.280
[Guest]: to hope that some form of healing happens after I leave. But you can never be certain about that.

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:40.240
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what you earlier said about sort of that your general demeanor is sort of not to be

00:41:40.240 --> 00:41:44.240
[Amit Varma]: affected by this and you just get the work done and you're affected by it. I'm also struck by

00:41:44.240 --> 00:41:48.320
[Amit Varma]: someone who told me an identical thing. I don't know if you heard that episode, Amardeep Singh,

00:41:48.320 --> 00:41:54.080
[Amit Varma]: the historian of Nanak's Travels and so on. And, you know, I did an episode with him and he

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:59.040
[Amit Varma]: spoke about how he went to Mirpur once, where if I remember correctly, many of his family had...

00:41:59.040 --> 00:42:03.920
[Guest]: His family is from Muzaffarabad actually. I know him well and I know his work well,

00:42:03.920 --> 00:42:06.640
[Guest]: but this particular story is also from Mirpur.

00:42:06.640 --> 00:42:11.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. So how he went to Mirpur and some distant members of his family or people he knew

00:42:11.920 --> 00:42:17.200
[Amit Varma]: were sort of things that happened there. And I asked him, you know, was it an emotional moment

00:42:17.200 --> 00:42:21.040
[Amit Varma]: to, you know, walk by the banks of the same river and all of that? And he was like, no,

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:25.280
[Amit Varma]: not at all. Completely detached. And it's later when you view the tapes and you

00:42:25.280 --> 00:42:29.280
[Amit Varma]: go through the equipment again, that the emotion really happens. That struck me.

00:42:29.280 --> 00:42:34.000
[Amit Varma]: The other thing that kind of struck me and just take me through your process of making the choices

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:39.040
[Amit Varma]: you made here is that, you know, while speaking during this brief conversation so far, you've,

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:44.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, used these phrases like body ko dispose kar diya aur us zamane mein halat hi aise the.

00:42:44.560 --> 00:42:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And these words have a flavor, which is very hard to capture in pure English or it's very,

00:42:50.240 --> 00:42:53.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, I think a lot of the language would be very hard to capture. And what you have,

00:42:53.920 --> 00:42:59.360
[Amit Varma]: of course, done is while, you know, most of it is in very clear and evocative English,

00:43:00.160 --> 00:43:05.040
[Amit Varma]: you also use, you know, many bits of the original Punjabi or whatever for the flavor,

00:43:05.040 --> 00:43:08.960
[Amit Varma]: which I sort of appreciated because I think that, you know, gave me a sense of,

00:43:09.680 --> 00:43:13.600
[Amit Varma]: it's almost like you hear the person speaking and that's also very evocative.

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:17.760
[Amit Varma]: So how do you then make those choices of what to do about the language? Because the thing is,

00:43:17.760 --> 00:43:21.280
[Amit Varma]: it's not that you're just listening to one or two languages, you're listening to Punjabi and

00:43:21.280 --> 00:43:27.360
[Amit Varma]: Urdu and Hindi, but you're listening to all kinds of different ways of speaking. Like you,

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:31.600
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned someone you met in Pakistan, who was talking in a particular Patiala kind of

00:43:31.600 --> 00:43:35.360
[Amit Varma]: accent and whatever. And, but then you are writing a book in English,

00:43:35.360 --> 00:43:39.920
[Amit Varma]: or even if you're doing an art project, whatever there is accompanying it is in English. So how do

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:45.280
[Amit Varma]: you make these choices that, how do I get this flavor across? Because it is impossible to

00:43:45.280 --> 00:43:49.840
[Guest]: translate, right? So... I think it connects to what you were originally saying about writing

00:43:49.840 --> 00:43:55.600
[Guest]: for foreign papers. Why do you need to write? I mean, I guess the question is, are you not

00:43:55.600 --> 00:44:00.800
[Guest]: writing for your own people? And if you are writing for your own people, then put something

00:44:00.800 --> 00:44:06.080
[Guest]: in there that they will relate to. English is not our language. English is a language that I think

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:14.880
[Guest]: in. English is my first language. But for so many of us, the past is rendered through regional

00:44:14.880 --> 00:44:19.600
[Guest]: languages. And while I realized that I couldn't write a book entirely in regional languages,

00:44:20.320 --> 00:44:26.160
[Guest]: there are some things that I wouldn't say are untranslatable, but I would say that they don't

00:44:26.160 --> 00:44:32.640
[Guest]: get the significance of the experience across as well in English. I'll give you an example,

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:37.600
[Guest]: you gave several. I'll give you another one. The same woman who was talking about Patiala and

00:44:37.600 --> 00:44:43.840
[Guest]: Samana said, woh hum takseeme hin kabhi bhula nahi paayenge. To which I translate, I'll never

00:44:43.840 --> 00:44:49.280
[Guest]: forget the partition of India. But it's not the same. It's not the same because takseeme hin

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:56.880
[Guest]: carries with it a history. A history of hin and a history of that line. Takseeme toh line huni thi.

00:44:56.880 --> 00:45:02.800
[Guest]: It carries with it such a specific history that partition cannot, just the word partition in

00:45:02.800 --> 00:45:08.720
[Guest]: India, it cannot put across in the same way. So I think that the decision about language was

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:13.360
[Guest]: pretty conscious and I knew always that I was going to do it. There was just no question about

00:45:13.360 --> 00:45:19.360
[Guest]: it. If you read my UK and US editions, they also have the exact same phrases because you're writing

00:45:19.360 --> 00:45:25.040
[Guest]: for your people. It is people's voices. And you know, with Indians and Pakistanis also,

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:30.240
[Guest]: we do this thing where we say things, we say the same thing in two or three different ways. So for

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:33.840
[Guest]: me, I know I'll say the same thing in Hindi, then I'll say it in Punjabi, then I'll say it in English

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:40.240
[Guest]: also. Or we mix our languages, which is quite unusual. Because I don't know if other people

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:44.640
[Guest]: in other parts of the world do this as well. So you know, to mix several languages within the

00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:50.320
[Guest]: same sentence. And I think that it's a part of, it's a part of our culture, isn't it like a part

00:45:50.320 --> 00:45:57.440
[Guest]: of our colloquial? So I did it as well. I did the same thing. Why not? I hate the sense that

00:45:57.440 --> 00:46:05.200
[Guest]: people don't consider their home market important enough. And I hate that because for me, the home

00:46:05.200 --> 00:46:11.840
[Guest]: market is where I do my research. It is people in the subcontinent, India, Pakistan, Bangladesh,

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:18.160
[Guest]: who give me the history, who give me access to their history. They are the most important for

00:46:18.160 --> 00:46:24.080
[Guest]: me, no matter how popular you may become in any book anywhere in the world. I don't think that

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:30.480
[Guest]: I would like to forget that I write for my people. And by my people, I mean in people in India,

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:33.920
[Guest]: people of Pakistan, people of Bangladesh, I don't see a difference in that.

00:46:34.880 --> 00:46:38.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, when you speak about how you write for the people of India, Pakistan, Bangladesh,

00:46:38.080 --> 00:46:43.200
[Amit Varma]: you don't really see a difference that we're all sort of one people. This is a quote from

00:46:43.200 --> 00:46:48.240
[Amit Varma]: your book, which I really liked where you quote Ran Neville as saying, quote, when Hindus, Muslims

00:46:48.240 --> 00:46:52.960
[Amit Varma]: and Sikhs broke sugarcane or ate aloo puri, they did so in the same fashion. When they went to buy

00:46:52.960 --> 00:46:58.640
[Amit Varma]: wares at Anarkali Bazaar, they did so together. This was, is a shared Punjabi culture, and it had

00:46:58.640 --> 00:47:02.480
[Amit Varma]: little to do with religion, stop quote. And you know, I had traveled, I'd spent a couple of months

00:47:02.480 --> 00:47:06.800
[Amit Varma]: in Pakistan in 2006, when I was covering the cricket tour there, I'd gone to all these places.

00:47:06.800 --> 00:47:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the first things that struck me, though it's a cliche, and I should

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:13.840
[Amit Varma]: have expected it, but it struck me was that I didn't feel I was away from home. Apart from,

00:47:13.840 --> 00:47:19.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, seeing Urdu signs everywhere, it was, one, I didn't feel I was away from home. And two,

00:47:19.200 --> 00:47:25.040
[Amit Varma]: it also struck me, again, that old cliche about how people contain multitudes, that the same person

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:29.440
[Amit Varma]: may be living in an Islamic state and maybe a believer and all of that. But at the same time,

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:34.160
[Amit Varma]: there is a Punjabi earth and there is a hospitality and there is all of that culture. So on the one

00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:38.560
[Amit Varma]: hand, you may have your president banning kite flying on a particular festival. But on the other

00:47:38.560 --> 00:47:43.360
[Amit Varma]: hand, that's what your community does, and you're jolly well going to do it. And it seems to me that

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:50.720
[Amit Varma]: what happens during partition is that a stress on only one aspect of identity, then it's almost like

00:47:50.720 --> 00:47:56.080
[Amit Varma]: you've spoken not just of the physical displacement, but also of the mental displacement.

00:47:56.080 --> 00:48:02.720
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that at some level, it's almost as if who you are is being partially partitioned,

00:48:02.720 --> 00:48:06.320
[Amit Varma]: where you're saying that this part of your identity is critical, and this is going to

00:48:06.320 --> 00:48:12.080
[Amit Varma]: displace you. And this is everything to us to the state now. And the rest of all of those things

00:48:12.080 --> 00:48:17.440
[Amit Varma]: which are common to you, how you eat aloo puri or how you bond over sugarcane juices is kind of

00:48:17.440 --> 00:48:22.640
[Amit Varma]: lost. And yet, it seems to me that many of the people you spoke to, you know, have sort of

00:48:22.640 --> 00:48:29.920
[Amit Varma]: retained an appreciation of that multiplicity of whatever makes them what they are. What are your

00:48:29.920 --> 00:48:35.360
[Amit Varma]: sort of thoughts? Do you see, like, did you see a lot of bitterness people slipping back into

00:48:35.360 --> 00:48:41.280
[Amit Varma]: sort of, you know, that aspect of what happened? Or was it just a sense of zamana hi vasatha and

00:48:41.280 --> 00:48:47.120
[Guest]: whatever? I mean, it depends. Now you can't generalize anything with partition and nor

00:48:47.120 --> 00:48:52.640
[Guest]: should you. And I think that we make the mistake not just with partition, but also in life to think

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:58.480
[Guest]: of people as binaries. So that if you're not this, you must be this. And if you're not that,

00:48:58.480 --> 00:49:03.040
[Guest]: you must be this, right? And this is unfair, because people have, as you mentioned,

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:07.360
[Guest]: multiplicity of facets within them, and they all contribute to making up that person.

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:12.400
[Guest]: It just so happens that at the time of partition, a lot of these facets may have been contradictory

00:49:12.400 --> 00:49:19.520
[Guest]: to one another. How do you live with that? And I think that this became most apparent in Pakistan,

00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:28.400
[Guest]: that a person could feel zealously nationalistic for the cause of Pakistan, yet deeply in longing

00:49:28.400 --> 00:49:34.800
[Guest]: of the home they left behind in India by choice. And this is very complicated. This is extremely

00:49:34.800 --> 00:49:42.160
[Guest]: complicated. Another interesting thing that I found there is that I would hear general statements

00:49:42.160 --> 00:49:48.000
[Guest]: like, usamane mein hindu toh bade intolerant thi, hindu ne yeh kara, hindu ne woh kara, which is so

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:52.720
[Guest]: similar to how we hear ya musalmano ne usamane mein yeh kara, ya musalmano ne usamane mein woh kara.

00:49:52.720 --> 00:49:57.840
[Guest]: And yet at the same time, here I was, a Hindu, sitting in Pakistan, in someone's house,

00:49:57.840 --> 00:50:04.800
[Guest]: obviously the other. First time I had felt like the other. And there people were saying,

00:50:04.800 --> 00:50:09.280
[Guest]: hindu toh us zaman mein yeh kar rahe the, woh kar rahe the, katal kar rahe the, lekin beta tum toh

00:50:09.280 --> 00:50:14.800
[Guest]: bilkul family ki dara. And I would say, par main bhi toh hindu, I am also Hindu. And they would say,

00:50:14.800 --> 00:50:23.520
[Guest]: mein hindu toh beti woh. So this, what does this tell us about people's psyche? It says that we

00:50:23.520 --> 00:50:31.120
[Guest]: are okay vilifying a community of people, particularly for an event in the past. But the

00:50:31.120 --> 00:50:38.000
[Guest]: minute a person from that community becomes a personal acquaintance, we find it very difficult

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:42.560
[Guest]: to put them in the same category. Which obviously means that large populations of Indians and

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:46.880
[Guest]: Pakistanis are okay saying Pakistani kharab hai or Hindustani kharab hai. But if they meet an

00:50:46.880 --> 00:50:52.640
[Guest]: Indian or a Pakistani, say in Switzerland or Canada or America, or even in Dubai, or even

00:50:52.640 --> 00:51:01.040
[Guest]: in their own hometown, the perception may change. It is the personal, right? I don't know, it's very

00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:07.120
[Guest]: complicated. These multiple notions of identity and memory and belonging and unbelonging. When I

00:51:07.120 --> 00:51:11.280
[Guest]: was doing the interviews, I wasn't thinking about any of this. But then you hear people make

00:51:11.280 --> 00:51:16.560
[Guest]: contradictions in their own speech, things like what I just mentioned. And you think to yourself

00:51:16.560 --> 00:51:24.640
[Guest]: that partition as an event is also a contradictory event. It made people make decisions that they may

00:51:24.640 --> 00:51:29.040
[Guest]: not have known completely at the moment. At the beginning of the conversation, you mentioned that

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:33.520
[Guest]: you were shocked by how little people, even in the governance understood what the word partition

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:39.680
[Guest]: meant. And till date, if I asked my grandmother about what exactly happened at the time of

00:51:39.680 --> 00:51:44.000
[Guest]: partition, and why did you move from your home in the frontier province to Delhi, a trip that would

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:50.000
[Guest]: have taken you three days to make, she would say fasaad the, dange the, riots the. But she doesn't

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:57.120
[Guest]: know where it started, what started. If you ask any common person from that generation,

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:06.800
[Guest]: have you ever seen an Englishman? They will more than likely say no. So the people that allegedly

00:52:06.800 --> 00:52:11.840
[Guest]: drew this line and allegedly divided the country and also propagated the idea of divide and rule

00:52:11.840 --> 00:52:18.480
[Guest]: were never even seen by common people. And I think that this should tell you the incredible

00:52:18.480 --> 00:52:23.920
[Guest]: disconnect that happened at the political level vis-a-vis the personal level. The people moved

00:52:23.920 --> 00:52:31.920
[Guest]: entire homes because of the boomers. Hawaayin chal rahi thi. Because of danger, because of fear,

00:52:31.920 --> 00:52:39.920
[Guest]: because of misunderstanding. And that's just heartbreaking. Which is why I say halaat the.

00:52:39.920 --> 00:52:44.720
[Guest]: It was the time. We didn't have enough news. We didn't have enough sources that we could trust.

00:52:44.720 --> 00:52:52.080
[Guest]: People weren't even educated. Ek badi mazedaar kahaani maine record kari thi of Burewal Mandi

00:52:52.080 --> 00:53:00.640
[Guest]: in Multan, where this woman tells me that ek radio tha and every day at 9pm that radio would be heard

00:53:00.640 --> 00:53:06.480
[Guest]: by everyone in the village. Hindu, Muslim, Sikh, it didn't matter. You would sit at that family's

00:53:06.480 --> 00:53:11.600
[Guest]: home. One family, Muslim family had a radio. You would hear the news. That is how we learnt about

00:53:11.600 --> 00:53:16.720
[Guest]: the war starting. That is how we learnt about the war ending. Second world war. That is how we

00:53:16.720 --> 00:53:23.520
[Guest]: learnt about partition. It was during that 9pm news that my brother was born and everyone celebrated.

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:29.200
[Guest]: And it was during that 9pm news that people became strangers and enemies. Because we were

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:36.080
[Guest]: told that partition is happening. How can you describe that? How can you justify that? I am

00:53:36.080 --> 00:53:40.560
[Guest]: still, this is the thing. I don't think that there are any answers to these questions.

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:45.600
[Guest]: That how is it that Hindus, Muslims, Sikhs, everyone from that village, men, women, children

00:53:45.600 --> 00:53:50.400
[Guest]: are listening to a radio every day. And then suddenly a radio broadcast tells them that

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:54.480
[Guest]: partition is happening and you need to go this way, you need to go that way. Do they become

00:53:54.480 --> 00:54:01.920
[Guest]: enemies? What happens? How does the creation of the other happen? I think that these are things

00:54:01.920 --> 00:54:08.480
[Guest]: that even people who lived through at that time are still trying to figure out. Just that we have

00:54:08.480 --> 00:54:12.400
[Amit Varma]: more distance from it. That's all. Yeah. And just sort of thinking aloud,

00:54:12.400 --> 00:54:17.040
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this goes back to what I was sort of saying earlier about the abstract versus the

00:54:17.040 --> 00:54:21.840
[Amit Varma]: concrete that, you know, some of the multitudes we contain, for example, we might be deeply

00:54:21.840 --> 00:54:27.600
[Amit Varma]: nationalistic, but in a toxic way at one level, but at another level, we are friends with everyone

00:54:27.600 --> 00:54:31.760
[Amit Varma]: we know and we behave very nicely with them and all of that. And it strikes me that one is an

00:54:31.760 --> 00:54:37.360
[Amit Varma]: abstract concept, that kind of nationalism and the grievances of the past and all that. But the

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:42.560
[Amit Varma]: other is a concrete thing, the people we actually know. So similarly, you know, when these gentlemen

00:54:42.560 --> 00:54:47.200
[Amit Varma]: sit with you and you're in their home and they tell you, oh, Hindus are intolerant, that's an

00:54:47.200 --> 00:54:51.920
[Amit Varma]: abstract statement to make. But you are the concrete Hindu in front of them. So they're like,

00:54:52.800 --> 00:54:58.000
[Amit Varma]: and the same thing about the radio. And the bizarre thing is that these people sitting together,

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:02.960
[Amit Varma]: listening to the radio, that community, that's a concrete thing. And yet, it is broken up by that

00:55:02.960 --> 00:55:09.120
[Amit Varma]: abstract notion of, you know, you are actually enemies and that sort of the dominance of the

00:55:09.120 --> 00:55:14.240
[Amit Varma]: abstract over the concrete. And you know, why we need these abstract things in the first place

00:55:14.240 --> 00:55:19.440
[Amit Varma]: is sort of, again, fascinating to me. And I'm just like completely thinking aloud here.

00:55:19.440 --> 00:55:24.800
[Guest]: So that's what I do every day. You know, Amit, like you could have heard hundreds of stories

00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:30.320
[Guest]: as I have. And you can hope that you come up with some concrete answer for why this happened.

00:55:31.040 --> 00:55:34.880
[Guest]: And I'm telling you, as someone who's trying to do it, there are no answers, there are only

00:55:34.880 --> 00:55:41.600
[Guest]: versions. There are only versions of what happened, which only tells you that, you know, no matter

00:55:41.600 --> 00:55:45.760
[Guest]: how many people you speak to, there'll be more versions, and more contradictions and more

00:55:45.760 --> 00:55:54.320
[Guest]: complications. But was it worth it? Was it actually worth it? If you ask India, Pakistan,

00:55:54.320 --> 00:56:00.720
[Guest]: Bangladesh, you may get different answers. And that's also a real, it's a real tragedy that

00:56:00.720 --> 00:56:06.400
[Guest]: the countries that partition happened to India, Pakistan, East Pakistan, later Bangladesh,

00:56:06.400 --> 00:56:12.560
[Guest]: and England don't have a shared official history of the event. So no matter who you ask, you will

00:56:12.560 --> 00:56:18.400
[Guest]: get a different answer based on their national allegiance. Yeah, and people will rationalize

00:56:18.400 --> 00:56:22.480
[Amit Varma]: and we don't know counterfactual. So it's just too complicated. I mean, I don't think there can be

00:56:22.480 --> 00:56:27.520
[Amit Varma]: a shared national history. I was kind of struck by the fact that, you know, you were musing on

00:56:27.520 --> 00:56:32.160
[Amit Varma]: this very same question long before your project started. I came across this quote in an old

00:56:32.160 --> 00:56:38.160
[Amit Varma]: feature on you by your friend Mayank Austin Sufi, the awesome blogger. And you had said at that

00:56:38.160 --> 00:56:43.040
[Amit Varma]: time, and this is 2010, when you're just 20 years old at the time. Was this with the horrible

00:56:43.040 --> 00:56:48.240
[Guest]: photograph of me with the bang in Jaan on a ship? Yeah, it took me a while to figure out that was

00:56:48.240 --> 00:56:53.120
[Amit Varma]: you. But they're really nice photographs. I mean, yeah. And you said, quote, I want to know why we

00:56:53.120 --> 00:56:58.640
[Amit Varma]: Indians and Pakistanis are so different as masses, and so alike as individuals. Stop quote. And this

00:56:58.640 --> 00:57:03.600
[Amit Varma]: has, of course, struck me every time I have actually interacted with Pakistanis, including

00:57:03.600 --> 00:57:09.360
[Amit Varma]: in Pakistan, where the, you know, the warmth I received was a bit too much. And that's something

00:57:09.360 --> 00:57:15.040
[Amit Varma]: that is, you know, visible in your book also, because you sort of intermingle all the chapters

00:57:15.040 --> 00:57:19.680
[Amit Varma]: with people who've gone there from here and people who have come here from there.

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:26.400
[Guest]: Right? That was a conscious decision, actually. And I decided that at a very early stage that

00:57:26.400 --> 00:57:33.840
[Guest]: I was not going to divide the chapters by Hindu, Muslim, or Sikh, or Indian, Pakistani, Bangladeshi

00:57:33.840 --> 00:57:40.320
[Guest]: or English. It was by alphabetical order. So if there were two women, one after the other,

00:57:40.320 --> 00:57:43.360
[Guest]: that was fine. If there were two Pakistanis, one after the other, that was fine. If there

00:57:43.360 --> 00:57:48.800
[Guest]: were two stories of shawls, one after the other, that was also fine. But it felt like the only

00:57:48.800 --> 00:57:55.120
[Guest]: fair way where anyone and everyone would get a chance to say what they had to say and be on a

00:57:55.120 --> 00:58:00.480
[Guest]: level feet. So I mean, I'm very clear about things like that.

00:58:00.480 --> 00:58:04.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I figured it was a deliberate, though not by alphabetical order, but I figured it was a

00:58:04.720 --> 00:58:08.560
[Amit Varma]: deliberate intermingling and that totally worked for me. Because sometimes I'd be reading a chapter

00:58:08.560 --> 00:58:14.720
[Amit Varma]: and I'd actually for a moment, I'd forget and I'd have to go back to the start of the chapter.

00:58:14.720 --> 00:58:17.040
[Amit Varma]: Alphabetical order of first name or last name?

00:58:17.040 --> 00:58:23.120
[Guest]: It was first name. And the only time I broke that was the first chapter, which is about the

00:58:23.120 --> 00:58:28.240
[Guest]: Ghazan Dukhara, which is a man starting with Y, my great granduncle. But it was the beginning of

00:58:28.240 --> 00:58:34.720
[Guest]: the project. So I figured that it was best to put it at the front. Otherwise, it's by first name.

00:58:34.720 --> 00:58:39.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, which is great, because, you know, you are, of course, Anshul and I'm Amit and I much prefer

00:58:39.680 --> 00:58:43.520
[Amit Varma]: alphabetical order of first name. There have actually been studies which show that

00:58:43.520 --> 00:58:48.160
[Amit Varma]: in the academic sciences, because you have the convention of going by alphabetical order of

00:58:48.160 --> 00:58:53.200
[Amit Varma]: last name, people whose names begin with the later letters actually do worse over time,

00:58:53.200 --> 00:58:59.440
[Amit Varma]: because in citations, it is the other guy's name, plus etc, or whatever. So I think was it in a

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:04.320
[Amit Varma]: Gladwell book that I read it, whatever, but, you know, more power to you. And I can totally see

00:59:04.320 --> 00:59:07.120
[Amit Varma]: why you do alphabetical order of first name.

00:59:07.120 --> 00:59:11.280
[Guest]: But it just seemed like it was the only way someone wouldn't give preference to one

00:59:11.280 --> 00:59:17.440
[Guest]: nationality over the other. And the point was, to forget who this person is and where they are

00:59:17.440 --> 00:59:21.440
[Guest]: coming from and to just focus on their story. And that's what I have done.

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:26.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. And it worked like a charm. Let's take a quick commercial break. And then when we

