[Amit Varma]: a drawer out of memory. Let's in fact talk about memory. I mean, which is also so fascinating to

01:01:03.680 --> 01:01:07.840
[Amit Varma]: me and you alluded briefly earlier in this discussion. And I've got a couple of quotes

01:01:07.840 --> 01:01:13.040
[Amit Varma]: from your book, which I also sort of want to ask you about. The first one goes this way, quote,

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:17.040
[Amit Varma]: if you imagine an experience to be the construction of a memory, then it's recollection

01:01:17.040 --> 01:01:22.720
[Amit Varma]: years later can be defined as this reconstruction. As the years pass memory inherently malleable,

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:27.760
[Amit Varma]: accumulates many perforations that can be filled with new experiences, imagine fabricated,

01:01:27.760 --> 01:01:32.000
[Amit Varma]: and sometimes even a seamless integration of several unconnected memories into one.

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:37.600
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, it is possible to change or alters one's original memory, depending on the conditions

01:01:37.600 --> 01:01:42.960
[Amit Varma]: in which it is recalled. And sort of before I come to the next quote, it sort of strike me,

01:01:42.960 --> 01:01:49.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, one of the things that I have, in fact, read recently about memory is that the first time

01:01:49.440 --> 01:01:54.560
[Amit Varma]: we remember an experience, we remember it. But the second time we are remembering the remembering it.

01:01:54.560 --> 01:01:59.600
[Amit Varma]: And like that, as we keep reconstructing it, we can sort of add layers onto it. And all of us,

01:01:59.600 --> 01:02:05.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, just assume that, oh, I remember it so well, and so vividly, and yet, memory is so

01:02:05.360 --> 01:02:11.120
[Guest]: incredibly flawed. So, you know, one thing that like, it's a very basic example,

01:02:11.760 --> 01:02:17.840
[Guest]: when you're a child, and you have a certain experience, and this has happened to me several

01:02:17.840 --> 01:02:21.600
[Guest]: times. And then when you get older, and you ask your parent, hey, remember that,

01:02:21.600 --> 01:02:26.240
[Guest]: that day that we did that thing? And they're always like, No, no, that's not what happened.

01:02:26.240 --> 01:02:31.040
[Guest]: It was like this. And you're like, No, I remember it was like this. And the parent is like, No, no,

01:02:31.040 --> 01:02:36.240
[Guest]: it was like that. So you're both thinking of the same memory, but it is mediated by your

01:02:36.240 --> 01:02:41.120
[Amit Varma]: newer experiences. Yeah, yeah. And you know, another of the things that we do know is that

01:02:41.120 --> 01:02:46.800
[Amit Varma]: so much of memory can be constructed by suggestion or, you know, by like you said,

01:02:46.800 --> 01:02:50.560
[Amit Varma]: you don't meet them a second time, because by that time, you know, they could be framing things

01:02:50.560 --> 01:02:56.400
[Amit Varma]: according to how what you want to hear and not necessarily even consciously. So what have you

01:02:56.400 --> 01:02:59.440
[Amit Varma]: learned about memory and all of this time, while while you've been doing this?

01:03:00.800 --> 01:03:05.680
[Guest]: What I've learned is probably contradictory to itself is that on one level,

01:03:07.200 --> 01:03:14.320
[Guest]: we cannot trust true memory, because there is no true memory. On the other level, memory is

01:03:14.320 --> 01:03:21.040
[Guest]: probably the most intimate source in building a personal past. There is no way that you will be

01:03:21.040 --> 01:03:26.320
[Guest]: able to furnish the lives of people with any form of academic history when it comes to partition.

01:03:26.320 --> 01:03:31.040
[Guest]: And so you have to rely on memory because you have to understand the perspectives and versions of

01:03:31.040 --> 01:03:37.760
[Guest]: what happened. So in that sense, memory is essential. Right. And your other quote about

01:03:37.760 --> 01:03:42.320
[Amit Varma]: the different kinds of memory, and I found this quite profound, where you said, quote,

01:03:42.320 --> 01:03:46.480
[Amit Varma]: there is the official memory of the state, one that strives to document the official facts and

01:03:46.480 --> 01:03:50.720
[Amit Varma]: figures. There is political memory, the kind that is recorded in newspapers, journals and the

01:03:50.720 --> 01:03:54.640
[Amit Varma]: political attributions of the time. There is geographic memory, the recollection of one's

01:03:54.640 --> 01:03:59.760
[Amit Varma]: soil, the kind of memory that gets lost within the sand and rain of a land that now possesses a new

01:03:59.760 --> 01:04:04.400
[Amit Varma]: name. There is a personal memory, which involves one's personal experiences. There is collective

01:04:04.400 --> 01:04:08.480
[Amit Varma]: memory, the memory of society of a people, neighborhood or family. And then there is

01:04:08.480 --> 01:04:13.520
[Amit Varma]: another brand, the kind that takes years to ferment, a memory residing between fact and fiction,

01:04:14.080 --> 01:04:19.280
[Amit Varma]: a diluted, malleable memory that encompasses all of the above, coupled with the key ingredient of

01:04:19.280 --> 01:04:23.840
[Amit Varma]: time. This is a kind of memory passed down through one's genealogy, a generational memory

01:04:23.840 --> 01:04:28.000
[Amit Varma]: that I and many others being descendants of those men and women who witnessed a partition

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:32.880
[Amit Varma]: have inherited. And, you know, you began the project in a sense by, you know, speaking to

01:04:32.880 --> 01:04:38.800
[Amit Varma]: your grandparents about memories that in a sense are part of your origin story as well. I mean,

01:04:38.800 --> 01:04:42.320
[Amit Varma]: had partition not happened, who knows, you wouldn't have been here. I know, I think about

01:04:42.320 --> 01:04:48.480
[Amit Varma]: that all the time. And I would have lost this episode. So been probably talking about policy

01:04:48.480 --> 01:04:56.240
[Amit Varma]: with some boring man. But anyway, yeah. So did you feel that, that in a sense, that if there is,

01:04:56.240 --> 01:05:01.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, a sense of self that also comes from collective memory, that, you know, listening to

01:05:01.440 --> 01:05:07.760
[Amit Varma]: these stories is also sort of adding to your sense of self in a way, I won't say adding to your

01:05:08.320 --> 01:05:12.640
[Amit Varma]: memory, as it were, but adding to your sense of self and who you are, and just adding a layer

01:05:12.640 --> 01:05:20.400
[Guest]: to the past? Yes, definitely. I mean, one thing that I would say is, it struck me how different

01:05:21.440 --> 01:05:27.680
[Guest]: the official memory was from personal memory. That's the first thing. Like, I couldn't believe

01:05:27.680 --> 01:05:32.800
[Guest]: the stories I was hearing was so different from the stories I'd read in textbooks and books,

01:05:33.520 --> 01:05:38.880
[Guest]: which obviously meant that there had been a gap. There had been a large void in understanding

01:05:38.880 --> 01:05:45.280
[Guest]: what happened to people at the time. But I think every single interview I do, whether it's with

01:05:45.280 --> 01:05:50.560
[Guest]: my family or someone else, it adds to an understanding of me being a person of this land.

01:05:50.560 --> 01:05:56.560
[Guest]: I don't know whether it adds to my memory, as you say, because, you know, these memories don't

01:05:56.560 --> 01:06:02.080
[Guest]: belong to me. As I said, even if they have been uncovered by me, they are not mine. But at the

01:06:02.080 --> 01:06:07.600
[Guest]: same time, I think it gives me a sense of grounding, in a sense of belonging to a certain

01:06:07.600 --> 01:06:13.600
[Guest]: place. So I'll give you an example. Before I went to Lahore for the first time in 2014,

01:06:13.600 --> 01:06:19.040
[Guest]: or Pakistan in general, for that matter, I had recorded so many stories of people in India who

01:06:19.040 --> 01:06:25.040
[Guest]: had lived in different parts of Pakistan, that when I set foot on that land, I did not, for a

01:06:25.040 --> 01:06:32.560
[Guest]: minute, think that I didn't know it. It felt so seamless, because I somehow knew its core, its

01:06:32.560 --> 01:06:38.880
[Guest]: heart, its heart was undivided India. And I understood that part. And I think I was open,

01:06:38.880 --> 01:06:45.360
[Guest]: so the city was open to me. And I never felt like it wasn't mine. So I think that in conversations

01:06:45.360 --> 01:06:50.720
[Guest]: with people, you can understand, you can understand in principle, in theory, in life and

01:06:50.720 --> 01:06:55.280
[Guest]: life and memory, the heart of undivided India, and it adds to you, of course, it adds to you,

01:06:55.280 --> 01:06:59.760
[Amit Varma]: how can it not? And you know, one of the chapters, which I like a lot, and for the, you know,

01:06:59.760 --> 01:07:04.080
[Amit Varma]: listeners, there are like 21 chapters, which are all incredible personal stories. I mean,

01:07:04.080 --> 01:07:07.920
[Amit Varma]: each of them could be a movie or a series on its own. So if there's someone from Netflix,

01:07:07.920 --> 01:07:12.080
[Amit Varma]: listening, kindly get in touch with Anshul, even if you have other authors on your list,

01:07:12.080 --> 01:07:17.600
[Amit Varma]: go by alphabetical order or first name. But the chapter of yours, which I really enjoyed,

01:07:17.600 --> 01:07:23.600
[Amit Varma]: was a one on Prabhjot Singh, which was one a fascinating love story, how all of that unfolded,

01:07:23.600 --> 01:07:28.320
[Amit Varma]: which I won't talk about, leave it to the reader to discover. And these two little snapshots of

01:07:28.320 --> 01:07:33.760
[Amit Varma]: memory. And one is where she says, quote, we scrambled in leaving the house as it was,

01:07:33.760 --> 01:07:38.160
[Amit Varma]: we had all been eating dinner, I had been making the chapatis on the open chulha. And with the

01:07:38.160 --> 01:07:43.520
[Amit Varma]: confusion of the convoy arriving, I even left the chulha on. I remember thinking only much later

01:07:43.520 --> 01:07:48.880
[Amit Varma]: about the fate of the chapati left over the open fire, stop quote. And this is such a fantastic

01:07:48.880 --> 01:07:54.800
[Guest]: image. Like she's a poet, these little things that she remembers. And you know, like,

01:07:54.800 --> 01:08:02.320
[Guest]: note that I met her at a very late stage in her life. Like I met her at late 80s. And then I met

01:08:02.320 --> 01:08:09.280
[Guest]: her three years after that. And then the next year she died. So the fact that she remembered these

01:08:09.280 --> 01:08:14.640
[Guest]: incredibly poetic, just okay, I'm not going to ruin anything, go on, go on to the second aspect

01:08:14.640 --> 01:08:20.480
[Amit Varma]: of the thing. No, no, I mean, just to sort of elaborate on this, I think it can happen in

01:08:20.480 --> 01:08:25.680
[Amit Varma]: everybody's life that you remember these little things, but you don't notice you're remembering

01:08:25.680 --> 01:08:29.840
[Amit Varma]: and it is a noticing of the remembering that I think makes you a poet. And you know, I'm going

01:08:29.840 --> 01:08:34.400
[Amit Varma]: to in fact, give this example to my writing students as an example of how you can, you know,

01:08:34.400 --> 01:08:39.280
[Amit Varma]: focus on the concrete and not the abstract and make something come alive. I think also the bit,

01:08:39.280 --> 01:08:45.360
[Guest]: sorry to interrupt you, also the bit when she talks about in the train, you know, everyone

01:08:45.360 --> 01:08:50.320
[Guest]: talks about trains, like everyone talks about how cramped the train is and how difficult it was and

01:08:50.320 --> 01:08:56.160
[Guest]: how suffocated and how afraid people were. But she goes on to give really concrete examples,

01:08:56.160 --> 01:09:01.760
[Guest]: like I'm wearing a black chadar. And through my chadar, the blood of other people is seeping in

01:09:01.760 --> 01:09:08.240
[Guest]: so I can see a pool of blood in my black chadar. That is how dark the blood was. And I think that

01:09:08.880 --> 01:09:14.480
[Guest]: like for those examples, those bring up such visceral memories, even if you may not have seen

01:09:14.480 --> 01:09:18.960
[Guest]: anything like that, immediately you know what she's talking about. No, and that's the second

01:09:18.960 --> 01:09:24.320
[Amit Varma]: memory I was referring to, which is just such an incredible, incredible image that she's left the

01:09:24.320 --> 01:09:28.560
[Amit Varma]: chapati on the chula and gone to the station with her family and they wait a long time for a train.

01:09:28.560 --> 01:09:32.720
[Amit Varma]: And when the train arrives is completely silent. And then they get in and they discover why

01:09:32.720 --> 01:09:36.720
[Amit Varma]: it's full of dead bodies, everybody's been killed, but there's no time to offload anyone.

01:09:36.720 --> 01:09:41.600
[Amit Varma]: So they make the rest of the journey with the dead bodies living in the dead together,

01:09:42.240 --> 01:09:46.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, and you have suitcases of dead people lying there. And as you described through the

01:09:46.800 --> 01:09:52.080
[Amit Varma]: black chadar, the blood and all of that, and it is just such an incredible image that I am just

01:09:52.080 --> 01:09:58.640
[Amit Varma]: amazed that no filmmaker has yet sort of picked me up. So kind of incredibly powerful. And of course,

01:09:58.640 --> 01:10:04.400
[Amit Varma]: like you said, she's a poet. So I guess that's sort of where it was coming from. But you know,

01:10:04.400 --> 01:10:08.720
[Amit Varma]: when you were writing it, is this something that when you were interviewing these people,

01:10:08.720 --> 01:10:14.240
[Amit Varma]: especially, is this something that you were looking for all of these concrete, vivid things?

01:10:14.240 --> 01:10:22.960
[Guest]: Yes, because I'm an artist. That is why like, I sometimes feel really sad for not

01:10:22.960 --> 01:10:30.160
[Guest]: spending time in the studio. But this is how it comes out. Because when you make,

01:10:30.160 --> 01:10:34.880
[Guest]: when you make a piece of art, you're looking for the concrete ways in which people can enter that

01:10:34.880 --> 01:10:40.640
[Guest]: piece of art. You're looking for the relatable images. Why would you not do the same thing in

01:10:40.640 --> 01:10:47.760
[Guest]: a writing practice? I was always looking for the images, always, whether it is in the way that

01:10:47.760 --> 01:10:52.720
[Guest]: people spoke, in the gestures that they had, in the way that light fell on them, the colors of

01:10:52.720 --> 01:10:59.280
[Guest]: their clothes, the colors of their hands, their hair. That was, I was preoccupied completely,

01:10:59.280 --> 01:11:04.720
[Guest]: because that's what my training has been to look for the details. And I think that in that sense,

01:11:04.720 --> 01:11:10.480
[Guest]: I'm very grateful that I don't have an education in either history or English or ethnography.

01:11:10.480 --> 01:11:18.400
[Guest]: Because I know that the way that Rembrandts is written, it just is a melange of the visual art

01:11:18.400 --> 01:11:23.200
[Guest]: and the textual practice. It is. And another choice that you made during the writing,

01:11:23.200 --> 01:11:26.000
[Amit Varma]: which I meant to ask you when I was asking you about the writing earlier, which I found

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:31.440
[Amit Varma]: interesting, is that you don't document what they say, you document the conversation.

01:11:31.440 --> 01:11:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So you're also sort of documenting your own responses to what they are saying. Why that

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:42.000
[Amit Varma]: choice? Because, you know, others have, for example, treated it differently and just taken

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:47.040
[Amit Varma]: the words and, you know, put nothing between those and, and the reader. And yet part of this

01:11:47.040 --> 01:11:50.400
[Amit Varma]: is also your journey of discovery and understanding which is coming across.

01:11:50.400 --> 01:11:58.240
[Guest]: I think that you answered the question. And it's about me. Of course, it's about me. It's about me

01:11:58.240 --> 01:12:04.320
[Guest]: learning about my history and other people like me. So why would I not report how I feel,

01:12:04.320 --> 01:12:10.160
[Guest]: even if that feeling is of naivety? There could have been no other way. Because if someone is

01:12:10.160 --> 01:12:15.760
[Guest]: saying something horrific, and I say something in response to that, like, how did you feel?

01:12:15.760 --> 01:12:22.320
[Guest]: That response is genuine. I can't imagine how it felt. I wasn't there. But I want to know.

01:12:22.320 --> 01:12:26.960
[Guest]: And I know that the reader who's my age is thinking the same thing. How did it feel?

01:12:26.960 --> 01:12:34.400
[Guest]: How could you do this? This story, Remnants, is about me. It is about my generation. It is about

01:12:34.400 --> 01:12:39.280
[Guest]: the generation who has inherited these memories without actual knowledge of what happened.

01:12:40.080 --> 01:12:45.760
[Guest]: And I always, I don't know, it makes me feel really sad that we hear snippets of these stories

01:12:45.760 --> 01:12:50.560
[Guest]: and we can never make sense of them because they were never told to us in full. Because there was

01:12:50.560 --> 01:12:59.040
[Guest]: so much shame and sadness and pain attached or fear attached to the telling of that story,

01:12:59.040 --> 01:13:05.520
[Guest]: that it was never told to us start to finish. I always ask, how do you begin the conversation,

01:13:05.520 --> 01:13:09.920
[Guest]: you know? And for me, it's always really weird. Like if I have to ask my grandmother something,

01:13:09.920 --> 01:13:14.640
[Guest]: or my father something about this time, it'll always be like dilly-dallying around. And at

01:13:14.640 --> 01:13:19.280
[Guest]: the end, when someone is getting up to leave, I'll be like, listen, tell me, you know that time

01:13:19.280 --> 01:13:24.080
[Guest]: that partition took place? And it's like this really heavy conversation, but I am missing my

01:13:24.080 --> 01:13:29.520
[Guest]: window of chance and I need to ask it now. But how do you begin? Like what are the words you use?

01:13:30.480 --> 01:13:36.960
[Guest]: And then is the onus of asking not on you rather than on the person who's witnessed it?

01:13:37.680 --> 01:13:42.640
[Guest]: We very unfairly say that we were never told stories. I was never told stories ever,

01:13:42.640 --> 01:13:50.880
[Guest]: never. But is that not, I should ask, I should have asked, right? So I think that all these

01:13:50.880 --> 01:13:55.360
[Guest]: questions that I'm asking in the book are questions I know people my age are also asking

01:13:55.360 --> 01:13:59.920
[Guest]: to their families and they're trying to make sense. So I get a lot of messages from people

01:13:59.920 --> 01:14:05.840
[Guest]: saying I employed the same methods you used in the book to talk to my family and it worked.

01:14:05.840 --> 01:14:13.200
[Guest]: And that's what you're doing. That's it. I mean, honestly, this may be a document for India,

01:14:13.200 --> 01:14:19.200
[Guest]: Pakistan, Bangladesh, but it is also a public service as to how one can ask questions in

01:14:19.200 --> 01:14:23.680
[Guest]: their family, difficult questions, questions that you're afraid to hear the answers of,

01:14:23.680 --> 01:14:28.400
[Guest]: questions that people are afraid to say the answers of. I don't know. I feel like this

01:14:28.400 --> 01:14:34.880
[Guest]: document will outlive me because it is for a generation. It is for a generation. That's it.

01:14:34.880 --> 01:14:39.120
[Amit Varma]: And also because I think, you know, narratives of the past shape so much of what is happening

01:14:39.120 --> 01:14:44.240
[Amit Varma]: in the present and history is weaponized so casually that I think, you know, history is

01:14:44.240 --> 01:14:48.800
[Amit Varma]: like this sort of play a part in, you know, highlighting the concrete over the abstract as

01:14:48.800 --> 01:14:52.800
[Amit Varma]: it were, and highlighting the lives of real people and what they go through. I was, you know,

01:14:52.800 --> 01:14:58.880
[Amit Varma]: struck by another sort of stand in your book that while on one hand in the present day, you are

01:14:58.880 --> 01:15:03.360
[Amit Varma]: making objects come alive for these people and exploring their lives and, you know, bringing

01:15:03.360 --> 01:15:08.160
[Amit Varma]: those objects alive. But on the other hand, one of the things that we realize through your book

01:15:08.160 --> 01:15:14.480
[Amit Varma]: in different parts is how living people can be treated like things because of circumstances,

01:15:14.480 --> 01:15:20.000
[Amit Varma]: how, you know, for example, in the chapter about General JN Sharma, he's talking about the time

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:25.120
[Amit Varma]: he was in the army at Rawalpindi. And he writes, quote, one day, a few of us were driving around

01:15:25.120 --> 01:15:29.200
[Amit Varma]: the city trying to keep the peace and we heard a baby's cry. The drains were all open in those

01:15:29.200 --> 01:15:34.800
[Amit Varma]: days. And so we stopped to find this one-year-old child abandoned in the drain. The boy's hands and

01:15:34.800 --> 01:15:39.520
[Amit Varma]: feet had been cut off, maybe by the writers or whoever, don't ask me. These were good Indians.

01:15:39.520 --> 01:15:43.520
[Amit Varma]: And by that, I mean, good Indians, good Pakistanis, good Bangladeshis, they're all the same.

01:15:43.520 --> 01:15:47.360
[Amit Varma]: But when they begin writing, when they begin looting and raping and killing the innocent

01:15:47.360 --> 01:15:51.920
[Amit Varma]: under the spell of unexplainable bloodlust, then they are the worst people in the world. It was

01:15:51.920 --> 01:15:56.560
[Amit Varma]: such an unthinkable act. And the boy's body must have been bleeding for a while since it lay in a

01:15:56.560 --> 01:16:01.360
[Amit Varma]: pool of blood. He hadn't died yet, though he was screaming in pain, a limbless body. I can never

01:16:01.360 --> 01:16:05.920
[Amit Varma]: forget that sight. And he goes on to talk about how one of his colleagues said, shall we shoot him

01:16:05.920 --> 01:16:11.360
[Amit Varma]: and put him out of his misery? And he can't get himself to do that. And later on, you write

01:16:11.360 --> 01:16:15.440
[Amit Varma]: completely from a sort of a different angle. When you're writing the chapter on Ajit Kaur

01:16:16.400 --> 01:16:21.520
[Amit Varma]: Kapoor, you write about how they are making that trip through the jungle that takes many days and

01:16:21.520 --> 01:16:26.320
[Amit Varma]: you write and you quote her as saying, quote, lots of people abandoned their children in the jungle.

01:16:26.320 --> 01:16:30.000
[Amit Varma]: So many small children could not walk. And so they walked ahead and left them behind.

01:16:30.000 --> 01:16:34.400
[Amit Varma]: So many families even buried their children in the forest itself. Stop good. And this is

01:16:34.400 --> 01:16:39.120
[Amit Varma]: buried alive. And you pointed out about how when she is given birth and the sword is used to cut

01:16:39.120 --> 01:16:43.360
[Amit Varma]: her umbilical cord, even they leave the child there and they walk a few steps before they hear

01:16:43.360 --> 01:16:49.760
[Amit Varma]: the cry and other instincts kick in. And this is that sort of treating a human life as if it is

01:16:49.760 --> 01:16:56.080
[Amit Varma]: suddenly in those extraordinary times, a life loses its values. And, and, and, you know, people

01:16:56.080 --> 01:17:02.080
[Amit Varma]: often think of partition as, you know, like you quoted that other person saying, you know,

01:17:02.080 --> 01:17:08.640
[Amit Varma]: whatever, but the point is that we are like this, humans are like this, that this is, you know,

01:17:08.640 --> 01:17:11.520
[Amit Varma]: if you look at what happened during the Delhi riots or the Gujarat riots.

01:17:11.520 --> 01:17:13.440
[Guest]: I was just going to say that.

01:17:13.440 --> 01:17:24.320
[Amit Varma]: And it, I think, you know, reveals a deep truth about human nature, perhaps that, you know,

01:17:24.320 --> 01:17:31.520
[Amit Varma]: all of our kindness and compassion is contingent and, you know, and, and into passion whipped by

01:17:31.520 --> 01:17:38.000
[Amit Varma]: abstract concepts, we can cause so much concrete harm as it were. Was this, I mean, was some of

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:43.040
[Amit Varma]: this a surprise to you? Did you have to steal yourself to take all of this in and process it?

01:17:43.040 --> 01:17:46.960
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, contextualize it to the modern time. Did you ever ask yourself,

01:17:46.960 --> 01:17:48.960
[Amit Varma]: what would I do? You know,

01:17:49.520 --> 01:17:56.480
[Guest]: All the time, I, to be able to put yourself in someone's shoes and feel what they are feeling

01:17:56.480 --> 01:18:04.160
[Guest]: called empathy. That's what empathy is. And I think that I did that all the time. So when

01:18:04.160 --> 01:18:09.680
[Guest]: Lieutenant General Sharma was talking about how it felt to leave that baby there. Of course,

01:18:09.680 --> 01:18:14.400
[Guest]: I was thinking about how it felt. Of course, I asked him how it felt. And you can only assume

01:18:14.400 --> 01:18:20.160
[Guest]: what his answer was because he was a, he was a real military man. And yet these things

01:18:21.120 --> 01:18:26.480
[Guest]: tore him up from inside. Right. Which tells us that there are contradictions within the

01:18:26.480 --> 01:18:31.040
[Guest]: most disciplined of people, which can tell us that there must be contradictions within the

01:18:31.040 --> 01:18:36.880
[Guest]: most nationalist of people. But of course, like you question everything. You don't think that

01:18:36.880 --> 01:18:42.880
[Guest]: when the Delhi riots happened, the first thing I thought of is partition. Of course, I don't know,

01:18:42.880 --> 01:18:49.680
[Guest]: like, I am, you can still feel the tremors of partition today and not physically only within,

01:18:49.680 --> 01:18:57.120
[Guest]: you know, places like Kashmir or the Northeast. You can feel it every day. You can feel it every

01:18:57.120 --> 01:19:02.400
[Guest]: day if you're looking out for it. And it is in the way that people have changed after partition

01:19:02.400 --> 01:19:09.360
[Guest]: in the creation of the other, in the way in which we treat human lives as worthless.

01:19:10.400 --> 01:19:18.000
[Guest]: Mob mentality is the same now as it was then. It is very difficult to extricate reason from that.

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:25.520
[Guest]: It's just that now we should have had more onus and we should have had more responsibility to

01:19:25.520 --> 01:19:31.360
[Guest]: think the other way. But we haven't. We haven't. And anyone, anyone who cannot see the comparison

01:19:31.360 --> 01:19:37.280
[Guest]: is not looking for it or trying very hard not to deny it. So one of the projects that I have

01:19:37.280 --> 01:19:43.440
[Guest]: been doing for many years on the side is to look at generational memory and to look at the ways

01:19:43.440 --> 01:19:50.400
[Guest]: in which people have been shaped by partition and how or what we feel. Because I think that

01:19:51.040 --> 01:19:54.800
[Guest]: a lot of people think partition memory ends at the first generation, but that's obviously not

01:19:54.800 --> 01:20:03.120
[Guest]: the case. And maybe a theory that I have, I don't know if it's like a, it's a form in a theory or

01:20:03.120 --> 01:20:12.160
[Guest]: not, but maybe people who have not felt the pain of partition are the ones that instigate violence

01:20:12.160 --> 01:20:20.000
[Guest]: towards the other. Because never have I seen or heard in the generation that witnessed partition

01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:26.800
[Guest]: or even 84 riots for that matter. I don't know any malicious words for the other side. You hear

01:20:26.800 --> 01:20:33.600
[Guest]: stories in Delhi riots of Sikhs that were hunted in 1984 and they are the ones who saved Muslims.

01:20:33.600 --> 01:20:38.560
[Guest]: What does it tell you? It tells you that people who witness violence do have the ability to look

01:20:38.560 --> 01:20:43.840
[Guest]: past it because they have witnessed something. They don't want someone else to witness the same

01:20:43.840 --> 01:20:47.200
[Guest]: thing. I don't know. This is just me thinking out loud. I don't know whether this is the case. I

01:20:47.200 --> 01:20:51.920
[Guest]: haven't done enough research to know whether this is the case, but I'd like to think so.

01:20:53.360 --> 01:20:57.760
[Guest]: I don't know. I don't even know where I'm going with this part actually, just to understand

01:20:57.760 --> 01:21:02.800
[Guest]: whether or not we can draw connections to the present and why it was so important for me to

01:21:02.800 --> 01:21:08.960
[Guest]: put myself in this book because the world around us has never been more uncertain in so many

01:21:08.960 --> 01:21:14.400
[Guest]: different ways. And I think that there are a lot of panels to be made with partition

01:21:14.400 --> 01:21:21.360
[Amit Varma]: and the birth of difference. So I have a related sort of big question relating to this, but

01:21:21.360 --> 01:21:26.720
[Amit Varma]: before that, just an observation on what you said that, you know, what you just said about

01:21:26.720 --> 01:21:32.080
[Amit Varma]: people who have experienced violence, maybe more wary of, you know, going down that route again.

01:21:32.080 --> 01:21:36.160
[Amit Varma]: I'm not sure I agree. And I would also say that perhaps there is a little bit of selection bias

01:21:36.160 --> 01:21:42.160
[Amit Varma]: there because one of the things that I noted through your book is that everyone you spoke to

01:21:42.160 --> 01:21:47.120
[Amit Varma]: was relatively very privileged and came out of it good. You know, they are the ones

01:21:47.120 --> 01:21:51.760
[Amit Varma]: who managed to build a life, who survived, who managed to build a life and who can therefore

01:21:51.760 --> 01:21:56.800
[Amit Varma]: have the luxury of forgiveness as it were, and, you know, can sort of suppress that their

01:21:56.800 --> 01:22:01.440
[Amit Varma]: bitterness, who can leave the bitterness behind. And I'm sure that's a thought that must have

01:22:01.440 --> 01:22:05.360
[Guest]: struck you also. Of course, the fact that you're looking at objects already means that you're

01:22:05.360 --> 01:22:10.960
[Guest]: looking at people who could have carried objects, right? And I would be the first one to admit

01:22:10.960 --> 01:22:16.480
[Guest]: all sorts of gaps in my own research. I mean, it's with people, you know, there's only so much,

01:22:16.480 --> 01:22:21.680
[Guest]: so many criterias you can take with people, right? So yeah, of course, there are many limitations.

01:22:21.680 --> 01:22:28.400
[Amit Varma]: That is one of them. Perfect. Going back to, you know, what you just said about these times are

01:22:28.400 --> 01:22:33.200
[Amit Varma]: more challenging than others. And they're more challenging in one more aspect, which you've sort

01:22:33.200 --> 01:22:37.920
[Amit Varma]: of hinted at in your book, though I don't know if you consciously thought of it that way. And that

01:22:37.920 --> 01:22:44.000
[Amit Varma]: is the aspect of how people relate to each other. For example, in your book, you've quoted Kizarji,

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:48.480
[Amit Varma]: one of the subjects of your chapters, saying, quote, in the old days, people used to care for

01:22:48.480 --> 01:22:53.120
[Amit Varma]: one another, ek doosre ki hamdardiya karte the, but now they only think of themselves. The

01:22:53.120 --> 01:22:57.680
[Amit Varma]: relationships between people have diminished between communities too, and especially between

01:22:57.680 --> 01:23:03.600
[Amit Varma]: our two countries. Taluk, Urdu ka lafza taluk, in English, you call it relation, aur Punjabi

01:23:03.600 --> 01:23:09.760
[Amit Varma]: vich enu kehnde hai jor jamna. Stop. My broad question for you, which also feeds into this

01:23:09.760 --> 01:23:16.640
[Amit Varma]: is that one in modern times, because life is faster and more fragmented, has community become

01:23:16.640 --> 01:23:21.440
[Amit Varma]: less important. And when you speak about today's times being more challenging than before,

01:23:21.440 --> 01:23:26.480
[Amit Varma]: I agree with that, but not just in a sense of what is happening around us in terms of politics,

01:23:26.480 --> 01:23:32.000
[Amit Varma]: because we have seen, you know, much of the 20th century, much of the world has, you know, been

01:23:32.000 --> 01:23:36.160
[Amit Varma]: through, you know, authoritarian dictatorships where millions have died. So in that sense,

01:23:36.160 --> 01:23:41.920
[Amit Varma]: this may not seem that new. But one way in which these modern times are different is that we are

01:23:41.920 --> 01:23:48.560
[Amit Varma]: more in this way, abstract ideas, forming these online tribes of people we never meet, doing

01:23:48.560 --> 01:23:53.120
[Amit Varma]: things in the virtual world, which we would normally not do in the real world, but who knows

01:23:53.120 --> 01:23:59.280
[Amit Varma]: if driven to it by these passions, we could even do them. But also what there is a sense of loss

01:23:59.280 --> 01:24:03.520
[Amit Varma]: is a loss of community. Like, for example, I have lived in the housing society where I live for

01:24:03.520 --> 01:24:09.440
[Amit Varma]: about seven years. And I don't know any neighbors apart from, you know, one of the neighbors on our

01:24:09.440 --> 01:24:14.080
[Amit Varma]: floor, we don't meet our neighbors, we don't hang around, there's no sense of community there. And

01:24:14.080 --> 01:24:19.600
[Amit Varma]: therefore, you're not putting real faces to people and having those real interactions. And even if

01:24:19.600 --> 01:24:25.840
[Amit Varma]: you did, as you pointed out in the example from Multan of all the villages gathered around the

01:24:25.840 --> 01:24:31.360
[Amit Varma]: radio who know each other and are still broken up by that. So do you think that sort of the greater

01:24:31.360 --> 01:24:36.720
[Amit Varma]: level of abstraction in our lives where we are interacting with real people doing concrete

01:24:36.720 --> 01:24:42.240
[Amit Varma]: things with them less and less is something that increases the dangers of sudden violence? Because

01:24:42.240 --> 01:24:47.120
[Amit Varma]: then where is the empathy? Where is the relating? Where is the, you know, looking at your neighbor's

01:24:47.120 --> 01:24:51.920
[Amit Varma]: kid and saying, oh, he's got a cold and let me give him something and just feeling that normal

01:24:51.920 --> 01:24:56.800
[Amit Varma]: everyday thing. So it's that, you know, I know, it's conservatives who will bemoan the loss of

01:24:56.800 --> 01:25:02.160
[Amit Varma]: community. But is that then a real danger? I mean, like, like earlier, you said, for example, that,

01:25:02.160 --> 01:25:07.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, millennials don't know how to listen. And, you know, to me, that's also part of what

01:25:07.520 --> 01:25:11.600
[Amit Varma]: is happening. And it's not the fault of millennials, or they're inherently worse people than

01:25:11.600 --> 01:25:16.800
[Amit Varma]: other generations, older people might feel that way sometimes. But just that, you know, these are

01:25:16.800 --> 01:25:21.040
[Amit Varma]: the imperatives of the time where our attention is so fragmented, and we have access to so much

01:25:21.040 --> 01:25:26.000
[Amit Varma]: happening in the world. Is that something you've thought about or that strikes any kind of thought?

01:25:26.000 --> 01:25:32.000
[Guest]: The loss of community is definitely ever present. But I have not thought of it in the large,

01:25:32.720 --> 01:25:40.560
[Guest]: in this very vast way. I think of it in very small ways in terms of the loss of my collective

01:25:40.560 --> 01:25:46.400
[Guest]: history. So a small example of that is when you go to weddings, Punjabi weddings, specifically,

01:25:46.400 --> 01:25:51.600
[Guest]: there are these aunties sitting with a dholak and a spoon, singing songs. I don't know these songs.

01:25:52.400 --> 01:25:58.720
[Guest]: I can't say these songs. I don't speak Punjabi. After these aunties are gone, who's going to sing

01:25:58.720 --> 01:26:08.800
[Guest]: these songs? So my worries are not always that large, my worries are smaller, and to my immediate

01:26:08.800 --> 01:26:15.200
[Guest]: life. But maybe you're right, maybe you're right, this drifting apart, this loss of community,

01:26:15.200 --> 01:26:24.320
[Guest]: this fact that we don't find commonality with neighbors anymore, or not even friends with our

01:26:24.320 --> 01:26:31.600
[Guest]: neighbors anymore, you know, maybe it is, maybe it is part of it. Yes, perhaps you're right.

01:26:32.160 --> 01:26:36.480
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, just kind of thinking aloud and sort of inverting the lament about, you know,

01:26:36.480 --> 01:26:40.960
[Amit Varma]: aunties singing Punjabi songs. And I guess why that would feel like a loss is because those

01:26:40.960 --> 01:26:46.960
[Amit Varma]: Punjabi songs carry so much else with them rather than the words in the music. But they carry all

01:26:46.960 --> 01:26:52.160
[Amit Varma]: of that for the people who are singing them or who remember them. And maybe it is not a loss if a

01:26:52.160 --> 01:26:56.960
[Amit Varma]: generation grows up without ever having heard them, they might have their own version, modern

01:26:56.960 --> 01:27:02.400
[Amit Varma]: current day versions of that just to think aloud, not to say that it is not a loss. Anything that

01:27:02.400 --> 01:27:08.320
[Amit Varma]: is lost is of course a loss. But, you know, so much of what is lost is a loss because of all

01:27:08.320 --> 01:27:14.640
[Amit Varma]: these other sort of resonances that they contain. And those resonances are, you know, dependent on

01:27:14.640 --> 01:27:19.200
[Amit Varma]: someone feeling the resonance. It's like, you know, the poet Vijay Sheshadri wrote this beautiful

01:27:19.200 --> 01:27:24.240
[Amit Varma]: poem, The Mountain at the End of the Universe, where the poem was basically about if there is

01:27:24.240 --> 01:27:28.080
[Amit Varma]: a mountain at the end of the universe, and it's the only thing that is there, then how can you

01:27:28.080 --> 01:27:34.000
[Amit Varma]: say whether it is a big mountain or a small mountain? I'm sorry, this is a ludicrous digression

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:38.480
[Guest]: it's not a question at all. I mean, it's right, I guess, you know, if there is something else

01:27:38.480 --> 01:27:44.880
[Guest]: taking the place within generations of something that's lost, then maybe it makes up for it. For

01:27:44.880 --> 01:27:53.040
[Guest]: me, like the Punjabi songs and stuff, lose them. It's just a connection with a certain place that's

01:27:53.040 --> 01:27:57.760
[Guest]: being lost in a certain time. And, you know, really, like, it's my responsibility to learn.

01:27:57.760 --> 01:28:05.360
[Guest]: But, in some parts, it's also the responsibility of elders to say, you know, so it's a dual

01:28:05.360 --> 01:28:10.800
[Guest]: responsibility. But for me, I always feel, I always feel it.

01:28:10.800 --> 01:28:14.800
[Amit Varma]: And is in a way, YouTube keeping it alive, because I remember all through my childhood,

01:28:14.800 --> 01:28:19.120
[Amit Varma]: and I was born and I spent the first 12 years of my life in Chandigarh before I moved away,

01:28:19.120 --> 01:28:23.680
[Amit Varma]: and I'm like half Punjabi, half Bengali. But all through my childhood, I never remember hearing

01:28:23.680 --> 01:28:29.760
[Amit Varma]: any tappe. But recently, I've come across tappe on YouTube, they went viral, because it was this

01:28:29.760 --> 01:28:33.920
[Amit Varma]: very charming couple which at their wedding were, you know, doing tappe to each other in the whole

01:28:33.920 --> 01:28:38.800
[Amit Varma]: Jagjit Singh Chitra Singh style. And, you know, so maybe who knows, these technologies will keep

01:28:38.800 --> 01:28:43.280
[Amit Varma]: these long tails of culture alive and help them find new audiences.

01:28:43.280 --> 01:28:48.320
[Guest]: I feel like also technology and social media help in, just like now, because we live in a

01:28:48.320 --> 01:28:54.080
[Guest]: digital age, they help in breaking a lot of myths about the other side as well. So that's another,

01:28:54.800 --> 01:29:00.560
[Guest]: I have depended a lot on social media and technology to get contacts for the other side.

01:29:01.280 --> 01:29:06.320
[Guest]: So yeah, definitely. But digital means we can become more connected to the past.

01:29:07.520 --> 01:29:13.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I used to love TikTok for that reason. I mean, it's, I taught a course called TikTok

01:29:13.520 --> 01:29:17.840
[Amit Varma]: in Indian society, I think it's a great tragedy that is lost, because it just empowered so many

01:29:17.840 --> 01:29:22.560
[Amit Varma]: people and give them a platform and also, you know, give them the sense that there are other people

01:29:22.560 --> 01:29:27.520
[Amit Varma]: like them. And that and therefore give them the confidence to produce content, which other people

01:29:27.520 --> 01:29:32.640
[Amit Varma]: would watch. So I think it's, it's fashionable in some circles to mock TikTok. But I just think it

01:29:32.640 --> 01:29:36.800
[Amit Varma]: was sort of incredible in that sense. And you can't take that effect for granted, the technology

01:29:36.800 --> 01:29:41.520
[Amit Varma]: came about and you had that cultural effect. And you had sort of preference cascades, where

01:29:41.520 --> 01:29:47.120
[Amit Varma]: especially I mean, I saw that in the LGBTQI community, where there was so much emboldened

01:29:47.120 --> 01:29:52.160
[Amit Varma]: self expression now happening. And, you know, which is that that's that's kind of an up going

01:29:52.160 --> 01:29:57.600
[Amit Varma]: that's a great tragedy. I want to shift now to talking about people's conception of spaces,

01:29:57.600 --> 01:30:01.920
[Amit Varma]: especially the places that they come from, you know, the small geographies, as it were the

01:30:01.920 --> 01:30:06.560
[Amit Varma]: intricate memories of childhood places that they describe, for example, again, I'm quoting from

01:30:06.560 --> 01:30:12.160
[Amit Varma]: your book, where you write, Balbir Singh Bir, born in Silanwadi, close to Sargodha, drew a map of

01:30:12.160 --> 01:30:17.360
[Amit Varma]: his city from memory in my notebook. It was detailed beyond imagination for a place he had fled 70

01:30:17.360 --> 01:30:22.000
[Amit Varma]: years ago, complete with where the neem trees grow, where the grain market was, and where the

01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:26.320
[Amit Varma]: boys of the government school set up by the British celebrated the victory of the Allied forces during

01:30:26.320 --> 01:30:31.200
[Amit Varma]: World War Two. When I asked him if he wished to go back, he smiled softly. Man toh karta hai,

01:30:31.200 --> 01:30:35.840
[Amit Varma]: it is my heart's desire to find a way home. But now I have no strength, neither in my heart nor

01:30:35.840 --> 01:30:40.800
[Amit Varma]: in my body. But memory that is a saving grace. And so I close my eyes and I make the journey back.

01:30:40.800 --> 01:30:46.880
[Amit Varma]: Every single day I plunge into the heart of my memory, arroz. And, you know, even in other parts

01:30:46.880 --> 01:30:50.960
[Amit Varma]: of your book, like you, you ask someone, I think, to describe Jalandhar and they pause for a moment

01:30:50.960 --> 01:30:56.160
[Amit Varma]: and said, Oh, I can't describe Jalandhar, but I'll tell you what was around my house, which also

01:30:56.160 --> 01:31:01.920
[Amit Varma]: strikes me that, you know, when we are using these sort of general terms like Jalandhar or Ketpeta

01:31:01.920 --> 01:31:08.400
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, you know, we are not actually talking about that city in the way any other individual in

01:31:08.400 --> 01:31:14.800
[Amit Varma]: the world would. We are talking about our own sort of special experience of it, which is real only

01:31:14.800 --> 01:31:19.680
[Amit Varma]: in our memories. Therefore, it's nowhere, it's not even in Pakistan. And that's something I've

01:31:19.680 --> 01:31:24.320
[Amit Varma]: also felt when I revisited places from my childhood, like my college auditorium, where I

01:31:24.320 --> 01:31:28.240
[Amit Varma]: went a few years back as an adult, and I was like, what the hell happened here? This was such a big

01:31:28.240 --> 01:31:35.120
[Amit Varma]: place? Why is it so small and dingy? And is there something very poignant in that, that you know,

01:31:35.120 --> 01:31:40.640
[Amit Varma]: that what they remember was never really there? It was, you know, are all the places that we know

01:31:40.640 --> 01:31:45.280
[Amit Varma]: really constructed in our memory, in a sense, even if we haven't been through a partition and

01:31:46.080 --> 01:31:51.360
[Guest]: actually been the space? Yes, I call it the imagined landscape, a very concrete term for me,

01:31:52.400 --> 01:31:58.480
[Guest]: the house of the past will always be more romantic, because it doesn't exist. It doesn't exist.

01:31:59.680 --> 01:32:03.840
[Guest]: In this case, with partition, it literally doesn't exist, because you're always you're

01:32:03.840 --> 01:32:09.040
[Guest]: holding on to the childhood notion of things, which is always beautiful. It is untouched by

01:32:09.040 --> 01:32:16.720
[Guest]: tragedy. It is, as you said, itna bada lagta tha, ab itna chota hai, you know, and, you know,

01:32:16.720 --> 01:32:22.000
[Guest]: several people point this out in the book as well. Preet Singh says that when I was in Quetta as a

01:32:22.000 --> 01:32:26.720
[Guest]: child, the Gurdwara was huge. But then she reads things and says, maybe it seemed huge to me,

01:32:26.720 --> 01:32:34.240
[Guest]: because I was a child. Or so many other people, he went back to their home, Faiz Ravani goes back to

01:32:34.240 --> 01:32:39.680
[Guest]: Jalandhar, and he says that I thought that the city was so big, but within five minutes, I was

01:32:39.680 --> 01:32:47.680
[Guest]: at my home doorstep, you know. So I think we hold on to things from our childhood in terms of

01:32:47.680 --> 01:32:53.360
[Guest]: geographic spaces, and they may be very different when we encounter them again. Maybe that's one of

01:32:53.360 --> 01:32:58.480
[Guest]: the reasons why people don't want to go back, right? Balbir Singh Veer, who sadly actually

01:32:58.480 --> 01:33:05.120
[Guest]: passed away this year because of COVID, he didn't want to go back because he had no need to go back.

01:33:14.160 --> 01:33:18.160
[Guest]: That's also one thing that one has to reckon with, right? That it may be very different.

01:33:18.160 --> 01:33:23.440
[Guest]: Faiz Ravani goes back to Jalandhar, and he goes to the graveyard where his father and sister are

01:33:23.440 --> 01:33:29.040
[Guest]: buried. And he says, there was an apartment complex there. So I paid my respects to the

01:33:29.040 --> 01:33:37.440
[Guest]: apartment complex. You know, the house in the past is always more beautiful, and always in some ways,

01:33:38.160 --> 01:33:43.360
[Guest]: full of happiness. Because it doesn't exist anymore. It doesn't exist.

01:33:43.360 --> 01:33:49.440
[Amit Varma]: And is the landscape you occupy in the present also an imaginary landscape, to use your term?

01:33:49.440 --> 01:33:55.200
[Guest]: That depends on our perspective. What you can touch is tangible. What you can see is real.

01:33:55.200 --> 01:33:58.720
[Guest]: But sometimes you have to see things to believe them. And sometimes you have to believe things

01:33:58.720 --> 01:34:02.800
[Amit Varma]: to see them. I was in fact struck by another poignant quote, where you've quoted the architect

01:34:02.800 --> 01:34:07.760
[Amit Varma]: from Lahore, Noor Qader, writing about his grandparents from Jalandhar. And he sent you

01:34:07.760 --> 01:34:12.400
[Amit Varma]: an email about his maternal grandfather, where he said, quote, Jalandhar was his weakness.

01:34:12.400 --> 01:34:17.280
[Amit Varma]: Everything was forgiven if you were from there. My nana would even send his car to Jalandhar autos

01:34:17.280 --> 01:34:24.960
[Amit Varma]: in his adopted city of Multan. Stop quote, which was quite, tell me now a little bit about, you

01:34:24.960 --> 01:34:25.440
[Guest]: know,

01:34:25.440 --> 01:34:44.400
[Guest]: Please, please. Now, his daughter wrote to me recently and said,

01:34:47.680 --> 01:34:51.680
[Guest]: Yeah, so that's like hardcore, you know, keeping with the tradition.

01:34:51.680 --> 01:34:54.720
[Amit Varma]: And abstract Jalandhar as it were, but in a good way.

01:34:54.720 --> 01:34:59.680
[Guest]: Yes, absolutely. But you know, it gives people a sense of security. I was speaking to someone

01:34:59.680 --> 01:35:05.120
[Guest]: the other day, and they said something very interesting. They said that partition did not

01:35:05.120 --> 01:35:10.160
[Guest]: change who you married in many circumstances, because even when you met people after partition,

01:35:10.160 --> 01:35:12.960
[Guest]: particularly in Punjabi houses, the first thing you would ask is,

01:35:12.960 --> 01:35:25.040
[Guest]: They always sought out people that they knew, or were familiar.

01:35:25.040 --> 01:35:30.640
[Amit Varma]: That's so fascinating. Give me a sense now about what kind of items people chose to carry,

01:35:30.640 --> 01:35:35.360
[Amit Varma]: like some of it is accidental, like, for example, you've spoken about someone who has to leave at a

01:35:35.360 --> 01:35:39.520
[Amit Varma]: moment's notice to Mussoorie, and they imagine that, okay, it's like a brief holiday, and we'll

01:35:39.520 --> 01:35:44.560
[Amit Varma]: come back to Quetta or wherever they were, and they just carry a shawl. In your grandfather,

01:35:44.560 --> 01:35:50.480
[Amit Varma]: Balraj Bari's case, you've spoken about how their choice was a practical one of carrying utensils,

01:35:50.480 --> 01:35:54.720
[Amit Varma]: because they didn't know if they'll get fed, but they knew that they are likely to get rations.

01:35:54.720 --> 01:36:00.640
[Amit Varma]: So why not carry utensils to cook them in and then those utensils become such a repository

01:36:00.640 --> 01:36:05.280
[Amit Varma]: of history and memory and all of that. So what are the different kinds of objects which you found

01:36:05.280 --> 01:36:09.280
[Amit Varma]: people carrying when they were suddenly displaced, as it were?

01:36:09.280 --> 01:36:14.880
[Guest]: So what people carry will also tell you how much time they knew they had, or whether they knew

01:36:14.880 --> 01:36:19.520
[Guest]: partition was going to happen or not. If someone sent their entire household on the goods train

01:36:19.520 --> 01:36:26.240
[Guest]: beforehand, you knew that they had money, and they had power, right? And they would be okay.

01:36:26.800 --> 01:36:32.800
[Guest]: People like my grandfather, for example, they did leave at a moment's notice, but they went from

01:36:32.800 --> 01:36:40.800
[Guest]: camp to camp to camp, right? And they did not know where they would get to eat from. But my

01:36:40.800 --> 01:36:44.800
[Guest]: great grandmother, I don't know how she had the foresight. She took utensils because she had to

01:36:44.800 --> 01:36:54.560
[Guest]: cook in something. Now people carried all kinds of things, everything from mundane utensils,

01:36:54.560 --> 01:37:04.160
[Guest]: everyday utensils, to valuable things like jewelry, or plates of gold and silver, or cultural

01:37:04.160 --> 01:37:11.520
[Guest]: items of cultural significance like hamam dastas, or paan daans and khaas daans.

01:37:12.560 --> 01:37:20.240
[Guest]: And then totally bizarre things like a 15 and a half foot crocodile carcass someone carried,

01:37:20.240 --> 01:37:26.880
[Guest]: right? I think that's the most extraordinary object I've archived till date. And then also

01:37:26.880 --> 01:37:32.960
[Guest]: the means in which they carried it. There have been stories of people putting gold inside laddus

01:37:33.520 --> 01:37:40.320
[Guest]: because food wasn't confiscated on the way. Or there have been this beautiful story I recorded

01:37:40.320 --> 01:37:46.960
[Guest]: once about a man who put a small Guru Granth Sahib, tiny two by two inch into the folds of his

01:37:46.960 --> 01:37:53.840
[Guest]: pagdi, so that no one would take it along the way. I think that objects actually reveal a lot

01:37:53.840 --> 01:37:55.680
[Guest]: about people's circumstances.

01:37:55.680 --> 01:38:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And I was also struck by how also they reveal customs which also may be lost along with those

01:38:02.000 --> 01:38:09.840
[Amit Varma]: objects like you've spoken about, Nargis Khatun's paan daan, for example, which came down to her

01:38:09.840 --> 01:38:15.360
[Amit Varma]: and you've written, quote, one was expected to make a beautiful small paan tightly wrapped so

01:38:15.360 --> 01:38:20.000
[Amit Varma]: none of the ingredients fell out and then presented the guest would accept the paan, pick it up and

01:38:20.000 --> 01:38:26.080
[Amit Varma]: say adab in return, bowing their head politely. So, you know, the paan daan is not just a

01:38:26.080 --> 01:38:32.400
[Amit Varma]: utilitarian thing that you make paan in it, but it's also sort of the repository of a certain

01:38:32.400 --> 01:38:35.280
[Amit Varma]: cultural value and maybe an age past.

01:38:35.280 --> 01:38:40.400
[Guest]: And I think when you're saying, when you're quoting all these things, I can see how people

01:38:40.400 --> 01:38:45.520
[Guest]: said things like, mujhe yaad hai unhone adab kaise kaha aur unhone mujhe kaise dikhaya paan

01:38:45.520 --> 01:38:50.000
[Guest]: kaise banate, because she made a paan in front of me, you know. It was not the paan that

01:38:50.000 --> 01:38:55.520
[Guest]: I was expecting I would get because it was a very like, karwa sa paan tha, usme kuch

01:38:55.520 --> 01:39:02.160
[Guest]: meetha nahi tha. But she made this small tight paan because wo hissa tha, unke culture tha.

01:39:02.160 --> 01:39:08.000
[Guest]: Aur aurat ko paan banana aana tha. It was something they just had to learn aur chota

01:39:08.000 --> 01:39:13.600
[Guest]: hota tha, tight hota tha, thoda chula, you know, kattha. She told me all this. And I

01:39:13.600 --> 01:39:18.960
[Guest]: think that there's something quite ritualistic about that as well, right? Or even the lassi

01:39:18.960 --> 01:39:23.520
[Guest]: thing for that matter. Ki ghade mein lassi kaise banate hain? Ya hamam daste mein tum

01:39:23.520 --> 01:39:29.760
[Guest]: kaise peeste hoon cheezein? It's something very ritualistic and very, it's again a form

01:39:29.760 --> 01:39:33.360
[Guest]: of oral tradition, right? Passed down from one generation to another.

01:39:33.360 --> 01:39:38.400
[Amit Varma]: And I was struck by another beautiful thing she said, which, you know, where I'll, you

01:39:38.400 --> 01:39:43.120
[Amit Varma]: know, quote her from your book, where she says, quote, but the strangest thing was that

01:39:43.120 --> 01:39:47.920
[Amit Varma]: we never realized when it happened. Kab ek mulk khatam hua aur doosra shuru, when India

01:39:47.920 --> 01:39:52.080
[Amit Varma]: ended and Pakistan began. There were no obvious differences between one land and its

01:39:52.080 --> 01:39:56.080
[Amit Varma]: conjoined neighbor. And so I suspect that we gained our new citizenship in a moment

01:39:56.080 --> 01:40:01.040
[Amit Varma]: curiously lost on us. Tucked away in the corner of an overcrowded train, we had quietly

01:40:01.040 --> 01:40:05.280
[Amit Varma]: become Pakistani. And there's an echo of this also in an interview of yours, where you

01:40:05.280 --> 01:40:09.680
[Amit Varma]: say about how you decided to cross the border by foot and go. And while you were checking

01:40:09.680 --> 01:40:12.960
[Amit Varma]: your documents, you suddenly realized that, hey, you'd already crossed over the line.

01:40:12.960 --> 01:40:17.440
[Guest]: Yeah. And you know, I wanted to savor that moment that like crossing over is such a

01:40:17.440 --> 01:40:22.880
[Guest]: reverential almost, it's such a big deal. Like you're walking across Wagah, you know,

01:40:22.880 --> 01:40:27.840
[Guest]: and it's just six inches. It's a white line. That's it. And ussi white line ke upar

01:40:27.840 --> 01:40:33.200
[Guest]: aapke your papers, your visa, your luggage, everything is checked. And before you realize

01:40:33.200 --> 01:40:37.520
[Guest]: that you've crossed it. And I looked back and India had been left behind. And I was

01:40:37.520 --> 01:40:42.560
[Guest]: almost alarmed because I didn't even realize. It's just like taking any other step.

01:40:42.560 --> 01:40:45.600
[Amit Varma]: And another aspect of what she speaks about is this language, Samanisha.

01:40:47.280 --> 01:40:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Tell me a little bit about that because that was so incredibly fascinating. Like just

01:40:51.280 --> 01:40:56.080
[Amit Varma]: a few days ago, I recorded an episode with Rajat Ubekar, where he told me about this

01:40:56.080 --> 01:41:00.160
[Amit Varma]: language in Nagaland he came across, which is not documented anywhere called Nagamese,

01:41:00.160 --> 01:41:04.640
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, which came about through a combination of Naga and Assamese and later

01:41:04.640 --> 01:41:09.280
[Amit Varma]: Bihari influences, and how you have all these different ways of speaking because you have

01:41:09.280 --> 01:41:14.720
[Amit Varma]: Indo Aryan, Austro Asiatic and Tibeto Burmese language families kind of colliding in that

01:41:14.720 --> 01:41:18.960
[Amit Varma]: space. And equally, you know, we tend to think of these languages as specific things.

01:41:20.960 --> 01:41:25.440
[Amit Varma]: But the truth is Urdu and Hindi are both in a manner of speaking, not just constantly evolving,

01:41:25.440 --> 01:41:29.600
[Amit Varma]: but very recent. And it's not long back that they were one thing and they were Hindustani.

01:41:29.600 --> 01:41:34.560
[Amit Varma]: And there are so many different ways of speaking. And tell me a little bit about Samanishahi.

01:41:34.560 --> 01:41:39.920
[Guest]: And, you know, the interview with Narges Khatun was in Lahore. And, you know, she was a very,

01:41:41.040 --> 01:41:46.720
[Guest]: I would say that she began as a shy interviewee. And I hadn't planned on interviewing her until

01:41:46.720 --> 01:41:52.000
[Guest]: after our dinner. So I went to see the family at the home, we had dinner. And in the middle of the

01:41:52.000 --> 01:42:01.760
[Guest]: dinner only, she just kept looking at me. Whereas her family's actually quite cosmopolitan. And yet

01:42:01.760 --> 01:42:06.320
[Guest]: the first thing she asked me was, have you ever been to Patiala? It was almost very stern,

01:42:06.320 --> 01:42:11.440
[Guest]: you know, and like, if you say no, then I'm judging you. But I said no, because I hadn't

01:42:11.440 --> 01:42:15.760
[Guest]: been. And then she was, you know, she was very quiet. And then I said, then why don't you tell

01:42:15.760 --> 01:42:20.560
[Guest]: me about your Patiala? Tell me, what do you remember? And that whole night she spoke in

01:42:20.560 --> 01:42:26.640
[Guest]: Samanishahi. I only realized it was Samanishahi after we had finished our conversation. And her

01:42:26.640 --> 01:42:32.560
[Guest]: granddaughter, Bano, asked me, did you understand that? I said, yeah, of course, I understood if you

01:42:32.560 --> 01:42:38.320
[Guest]: were in the room as well, didn't you? She said, I didn't understand it. Not entirely, because I

01:42:38.320 --> 01:42:43.680
[Guest]: don't speak Samanishahi. And I said, well, neither do I. And up until right now, I didn't know that

01:42:43.680 --> 01:42:50.000
[Guest]: it existed. What is Samanishahi? Samanishahi is a mixture of Hindi and Punjabi. And in that sense,

01:42:50.000 --> 01:42:57.600
[Guest]: it is a bit cruder than Urdu. It is a rural Hindi, which is mixed with Punjabi. And that is what she

01:42:57.600 --> 01:43:04.560
[Guest]: spoke. In fact, when Bano was growing up, both her nani and her dadi were from Samana. And they

01:43:04.560 --> 01:43:09.920
[Guest]: used to speak Samanishahi. And Bano, who had grown up learning Urdu, thought that these two dadi and

01:43:09.920 --> 01:43:16.880
[Guest]: nani had made a little language of their own, because they were uneducated. And they didn't

01:43:16.880 --> 01:43:21.440
[Guest]: speak pure Urdu. Whereas actually, they were speaking in the language that they came from.

01:43:21.440 --> 01:43:25.920
[Guest]: So the fact that I was able to understand what she was saying is because I was a Hindi speaker.

01:43:26.640 --> 01:43:30.640
[Guest]: And not all words are different, but some words are certainly quite different.

01:43:32.720 --> 01:43:37.680
[Guest]: And I just found it so strange that I am able to understand a woman speaking a completely

01:43:37.680 --> 01:43:44.240
[Guest]: different language than I do, solely because I speak one part of it. Whereas it just didn't seem

01:43:44.240 --> 01:43:50.000
[Guest]: any different to me. I mean, you would be able to understand it as well. But it was extraordinary.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:56.240
[Guest]: And I think this is the kind of joy of oral history and field research, because you discover

01:43:56.240 --> 01:44:02.160
[Amit Varma]: things like this. What I was also sort of curious to ask about is not just the objects that act as

01:44:02.160 --> 01:44:07.120
[Amit Varma]: a catalyst and as a sort of a gateway into the memories. But I noticed that at different parts

01:44:07.120 --> 01:44:12.560
[Amit Varma]: of your book, when people are sharing their memories with you, they are also talking about

01:44:12.560 --> 01:44:18.080
[Amit Varma]: missing objects. For example, in your wonderful chapter about Sumitra Kapoor, like first, I was

01:44:18.080 --> 01:44:23.600
[Amit Varma]: very struck by how she could date parts of her life because she said from the age of five,

01:44:23.600 --> 01:44:27.040
[Amit Varma]: because she said that that's when I started learning music and music was a peg for her

01:44:27.040 --> 01:44:32.880
[Amit Varma]: memories, which struck me that there is also music in a sense playing the role of these objects do

01:44:32.880 --> 01:44:37.760
[Amit Varma]: as a peg for memories. And I think with many of us, I mean, it's a common tendency to associate

01:44:37.760 --> 01:44:43.280
[Amit Varma]: particular songs or bits of music with memories. And that was fascinating. But I was also struck

01:44:43.280 --> 01:44:50.080
[Amit Varma]: by her sort of longing for her old pedal harmonium in Rawalpindi, that when she and her sister would

01:44:50.080 --> 01:44:54.240
[Amit Varma]: go back from school at one corner, they would start racing each other because they wanted to

01:44:54.240 --> 01:45:00.080
[Amit Varma]: play that pedal harmonium first, and they had to leave that pedal harmonium behind. And just the

01:45:00.080 --> 01:45:04.480
[Amit Varma]: fact that decades can pass and you can remember an old pedal harmonium, which you may not even

01:45:04.480 --> 01:45:09.520
[Amit Varma]: recognize if you see it, it'll seem like such a clanky instrument for all you know, but in their

01:45:09.520 --> 01:45:15.360
[Amit Varma]: memory, it's so precious. Was there a lot of that happening in the sense that it is not just that,

01:45:15.360 --> 01:45:21.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, these objects that they have now are an entry into their past lives, but that objects

01:45:21.520 --> 01:45:26.400
[Amit Varma]: really have that kind of meaning that we hang memories on them, and we remember them, especially

01:45:26.400 --> 01:45:33.040
[Guest]: the further back you go. Why the further back you go even now, right? I call these objects ghost

01:45:33.040 --> 01:45:39.040
[Guest]: objects, things that people wish they had carried, things that they left behind, things that they

01:45:39.040 --> 01:45:45.440
[Guest]: regret carrying and could switch. Like Maya Mirchandani's grandmother in her chapter, Savitri

01:45:45.440 --> 01:45:50.880
[Guest]: Mirchandani, I asked her, if you could carry something, what would it have been? And she said

01:45:50.880 --> 01:45:56.800
[Guest]: that there was a big swing for my child and I wish I could have carried that. So I think that the

01:45:56.800 --> 01:46:01.920
[Guest]: conventional boundary of the physical object has been surpassed in this book. That's for certain.

01:46:01.920 --> 01:46:06.320
[Guest]: Because it's not just about objects that were carried, it's also about objects that were not

01:46:06.320 --> 01:46:12.560
[Guest]: carried, objects that were stolen, objects that were missed, reminisced, longed for. And then

01:46:12.560 --> 01:46:19.520
[Guest]: there were objects that were deliberately foregoed in some way. There's a story in the introduction

01:46:19.520 --> 01:46:26.640
[Guest]: about a woman, a woman has narrated this story to me in Karachi, about a woman called Bua, who

01:46:26.640 --> 01:46:33.600
[Guest]: is migrating with her husband from Delhi to Lahore on train. And in the event of their migration,

01:46:33.600 --> 01:46:38.560
[Guest]: there is riots on the train and people come and her husband is killed and he's thrown off the

01:46:38.560 --> 01:46:48.080
[Guest]: train and he's bleeding. And she, Bua, jumps off after him and she's pregnant. So her husband is

01:46:48.080 --> 01:46:53.280
[Guest]: dying and he's basically losing blood and she takes off her entire chadar and she just soaks

01:46:53.280 --> 01:47:00.400
[Guest]: his blood in it. And then she leaves him to die there and she travels to Lahore by herself and

01:47:00.400 --> 01:47:07.440
[Guest]: she gives birth to her child and she buries the chadar in a grave, as if it were the father.

01:47:07.440 --> 01:47:13.760
[Guest]: And so there are objects of really precious nature that are given up for special circumstances.

01:47:13.760 --> 01:47:19.760
[Guest]: So I think that, yeah, the physical object is a very loose term in this case. Yes.

01:47:19.760 --> 01:47:24.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. I mean, I found that story incredibly moving and I somehow in a morbid way expected

01:47:24.880 --> 01:47:30.320
[Amit Varma]: her to keep the chadar, but, you know, soak with blood. But, you know, the chadar as a proxy for

01:47:30.320 --> 01:47:34.960
[Amit Varma]: her, the essence of her husband and therefore burying it and taking her kid every year to the

01:47:34.960 --> 01:47:42.000
[Amit Varma]: grave was sort of quite something. And another sort of moving bit was in your chapter about Uma

01:47:42.000 --> 01:47:47.440
[Amit Varma]: Sundi Amar, she moves from Lahore to Jalandhar during partition and then she later goes back

01:47:47.440 --> 01:47:52.480
[Amit Varma]: to Lahore and she's going to her old neighborhood and she stops somewhere to buy something at a

01:47:52.480 --> 01:47:56.400
[Amit Varma]: store. And the person says, you are not from here. Where are you from? And she says, oh,

01:47:56.400 --> 01:48:00.640
[Amit Varma]: I've come from Jalandhar. And immediately he says, you know,

01:48:00.640 --> 01:48:05.120
[Amit Varma]: Dhanji, tosi mutti bar mitti na leyan de. You know, because he's sort of come from there,

01:48:05.120 --> 01:48:09.920
[Amit Varma]: which was also kind of moving. You know, I'll leave it to my listeners to read your wonderful

01:48:09.920 --> 01:48:14.720
[Amit Varma]: book and discover much more of it for themselves, which even if they have no connection to

01:48:14.720 --> 01:48:19.040
[Amit Varma]: partition, you know, there's a lot in it that is so evocative and moving and thought provoking

01:48:19.040 --> 01:48:24.720
[Amit Varma]: itself. Let's kind of get back to you and your process of sort of writing this book. Like,

01:48:24.720 --> 01:48:29.760
[Amit Varma]: what was that like in the sense that, you know, I teach an online writing course where people

01:48:29.760 --> 01:48:34.560
[Amit Varma]: often ask me about the different sort of writing methods that writers have and how do they find

01:48:34.560 --> 01:48:39.440
[Amit Varma]: a voice, what is their discipline, blah, blah, blah. And I have to, at pains, I have to tell

01:48:39.440 --> 01:48:45.120
[Amit Varma]: them that, listen, there's no one method for doing it all, except that one thing common

01:48:45.120 --> 01:48:48.880
[Amit Varma]: to all writers who have written is that they managed to get their butts down and write

01:48:48.880 --> 01:48:54.000
[Amit Varma]: the damn thing. And how they do it, what hacks they use, this can vary. What's your sort

01:48:54.000 --> 01:48:58.160
[Amit Varma]: of system like? Like, you already mentioned that you didn't have the book in mind where

01:48:58.160 --> 01:49:02.080
[Amit Varma]: you were taking a lot of this material. So obviously, you're not going there with a

01:49:02.080 --> 01:49:05.520
[Amit Varma]: preformed narrative, you're going there with an open mind, and you're just trying to draw

01:49:05.520 --> 01:49:10.400
[Amit Varma]: what you can and, you know, get as many vivid images as you can. But later, when you sit

01:49:10.400 --> 01:49:15.040
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, looking at them, how do you then construct it? What's your discipline?

01:49:15.040 --> 01:49:19.680
[Amit Varma]: Like, did the sort of format for the book? Was it there with you from the start? How

01:49:19.680 --> 01:49:20.960
[Guest]: do you how did that work?

01:49:20.960 --> 01:49:27.280
[Guest]: So I always knew that the format was going to be conversational. It was clear. The minute

01:49:27.280 --> 01:49:30.160
[Guest]: I knew that I was going to write something, it was always going to be conversational,

01:49:30.160 --> 01:49:35.840
[Guest]: because it just felt most comfortable and most familiar. And most true to the actual

01:49:35.840 --> 01:49:42.960
[Guest]: experience of interviewing. I recorded my interviews in various languages. And just

01:49:42.960 --> 01:49:47.840
[Guest]: to get, you know, the process going, record the interviews, then I transcribe them and

01:49:47.840 --> 01:49:53.120
[Guest]: translate them into English. And then I start writing after doing secondary research specific

01:49:53.120 --> 01:50:01.760
[Guest]: to that person. So I should preface by saying that I was incredibly devoted to working on

01:50:01.760 --> 01:50:07.440
[Guest]: this, because there was a need to work on this. So in terms of either getting your butt

01:50:07.440 --> 01:50:12.640
[Guest]: down or inspiring yourself, there was nothing of that sense, because I had to do it. The

01:50:12.640 --> 01:50:17.360
[Guest]: book was born out of a necessity, because there was a void in knowledge. And so in that

01:50:17.360 --> 01:50:22.160
[Guest]: sense, I had to do it. And we also decided that the book was to come out at the 70th

01:50:22.160 --> 01:50:28.880
[Guest]: anniversary of independence. So there was naturally a deadline for it. The actual process

01:50:28.880 --> 01:50:39.680
[Guest]: of writing was, honestly, I had it already in my conversations. So I think that as field

01:50:39.680 --> 01:50:44.160
[Guest]: researchers, we are able to rely a lot on our conversations with people and they make

01:50:44.160 --> 01:50:51.280
[Guest]: up the bulk of our, our chapters. And I think because I had so much detail from people,

01:50:51.280 --> 01:50:56.320
[Guest]: so much sort of extraneous detail about all kinds of stuff, I was able to build that landscape

01:50:56.320 --> 01:51:01.840
[Guest]: as well. Not to mention the fact that I did a ton of secondary research about the areas

01:51:01.840 --> 01:51:10.960
[Guest]: that they specifically mentioned. I find it very daunting to think of a book. I find it

01:51:10.960 --> 01:51:15.680
[Guest]: really, really daunting to think of like a full book. So I always find it a lot easier

01:51:15.680 --> 01:51:22.480
[Guest]: to think of chapter by chapter by chapter. Because if you think in bite size, sort of

01:51:23.200 --> 01:51:30.800
[Guest]: graspable segments, then you won't get overwhelmed. And I hate, I hate to get overwhelmed. Like

01:51:30.800 --> 01:51:36.240
[Guest]: I'm a very, very meticulous person, I would say. So I took it chapter by chapter by chapter.

01:51:36.240 --> 01:51:40.640
[Guest]: And for the duration that I was working on any particular chapter, everything else didn't

01:51:40.640 --> 01:51:46.400
[Guest]: exist for me. Which is why you can have coinciding elements like child in Ajit Kaur's chapter

01:51:46.400 --> 01:51:50.800
[Guest]: to the child in Lieutenant General Sharma's chapter, and they don't have a connection.

01:51:50.800 --> 01:51:54.160
[Guest]: But they, if they have a connection, it's quite contradictory to one another.

01:51:55.840 --> 01:52:01.680
[Guest]: I think that writing comes easily to me. Like I don't want to lie about this. And I don't want to

01:52:02.960 --> 01:52:05.680
[Guest]: make up something when it's not true. Writing comes easily to me.

01:52:05.680 --> 01:52:11.200
[Guest]: The feeling also came pretty easily to me. I am a diligent note taker, which is something that if,

01:52:11.760 --> 01:52:16.160
[Guest]: if there are writers listening in on this conversation about, especially field researchers,

01:52:17.600 --> 01:52:24.480
[Guest]: make this a habit. When you are talking to people in the field, you have an audio recorder or video

01:52:24.480 --> 01:52:31.440
[Guest]: recorder on, but make it a point to take your own notes as well. And this could be maybe something

01:52:31.440 --> 01:52:35.760
[Guest]: they're saying resonates with you more. You know, it's going to be there in your recording, but you

01:52:35.760 --> 01:52:41.600
[Guest]: want to write it down because that is kind of the essence of their conversation. Or what I did was

01:52:41.600 --> 01:52:46.960
[Guest]: made a note of gestures, made a note of the light, made a note of the way they spoke, made a note of

01:52:46.960 --> 01:52:52.240
[Guest]: whether their language changed from one thing to another. For example, when my grandparents spoke

01:52:52.240 --> 01:52:56.800
[Guest]: to one another, it was always in Punjabi. But when my grandfather spoke to me, it was always in

01:52:56.800 --> 01:53:04.400
[Guest]: English. This is a conscious choice that he made. And it was up to me to discuss and understand

01:53:04.400 --> 01:53:11.280
[Guest]: why that was. So things like that. And you will find that your handwritten notes will not only

01:53:11.280 --> 01:53:16.960
[Guest]: make the story stay with you longer, but also help you to remember key aspects of that interview.

01:53:16.960 --> 01:53:21.200
[Guest]: Because if you're like me and you're doing say like hundreds of interviews in a span of six or

01:53:21.200 --> 01:53:26.320
[Guest]: seven months, you may not remember everything. So if you refer back to your notes, it will become

01:53:26.320 --> 01:53:32.000
[Guest]: a lot clearer. So that was that. But I think that the actual writing process, putting things

01:53:32.000 --> 01:53:38.400
[Amit Varma]: together, it was not hard. It was not hard. And where are you in regard to like, do you do

01:53:38.400 --> 01:53:43.200
[Amit Varma]: multiple drafts? Or are you just very meticulous with the first draft, revising every sentence and

01:53:43.760 --> 01:53:51.200
[Amit Varma]: paragraph as you go along? How does that work? Okay, so basically, your first draft has already

01:53:51.200 --> 01:53:57.920
[Guest]: been edited 40 times while it was being written in a sense. Yeah. And I think that I made a really

01:53:57.920 --> 01:54:02.000
[Guest]: good working system with my editor, every time I would finish a chapter, I'd send it to him.

01:54:02.000 --> 01:54:07.760
[Guest]: And that way, we made our deadline a lot easier as well, because it wasn't a big chunk like this

01:54:07.760 --> 01:54:12.560
[Guest]: is a 500 and something page book, right? It wasn't that that he was getting at the end, it was just

01:54:12.560 --> 01:54:18.720
[Guest]: like chapter by chapter by chapter, which actually just made it a lot easier for both of us. But

01:54:18.720 --> 01:54:24.720
[Guest]: I have certain things like, I know that a lot of people think, okay, I just want to get all this

01:54:24.720 --> 01:54:32.240
[Guest]: down. And then we'll start working on it. Like we just nuance it. I can't do that. What I do is I

01:54:32.240 --> 01:54:38.400
[Guest]: will make really detailed points about my entire chapter. So I want to talk about this, this, this,

01:54:38.400 --> 01:54:44.160
[Guest]: this. And then I follow that I follow that very meticulously, which means that yes, I may make 40

01:54:44.160 --> 01:54:50.560
[Guest]: divisions within the same chapter. But my first draft, so to say, will be something I can send

01:54:50.560 --> 01:54:56.000
[Guest]: to my editor and say, here you go. Now you can work on it. And given that it's your first book,

01:54:56.000 --> 01:55:01.760
[Amit Varma]: I guess, the journey through writing it is also a journey of learning how to write in a sense.

01:55:01.760 --> 01:55:05.760
[Amit Varma]: So you know, when you end the book, and I presume the introduction was the last thing you wrote in

01:55:05.760 --> 01:55:10.080
[Amit Varma]: it. Epilogue was the last thing I wrote. The epilogue. Okay. When was the introduction

01:55:10.080 --> 01:55:14.800
[Guest]: written? I'm curious. It was written after all the chapters. Yeah. After all the chapters. Yeah.

01:55:14.800 --> 01:55:18.080
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and I really loved the introduction. I love the chapters also,

01:55:18.080 --> 01:55:21.200
[Amit Varma]: of course, but I thought the introduction was fabulous. It just brought everything together

01:55:21.200 --> 01:55:24.800
[Amit Varma]: very well. So when you finish the book, and you look back on the writing that you've done,

01:55:24.800 --> 01:55:29.040
[Amit Varma]: say for the first chapter that you wrote in the book or whatever. Yeah, I thought it was horrible.

01:55:30.320 --> 01:55:35.280
[Guest]: So did you rewrite it? Or did you just say no? Um, I mean, I just thought that the quality was

01:55:35.280 --> 01:55:40.640
[Guest]: really different. Because I told you, right, I was sending chapters to my editor as I was going along.

01:55:40.640 --> 01:55:45.760
[Guest]: And I think even he saw that, as I went towards the later chapters, things became a lot

01:55:46.640 --> 01:55:50.320
[Guest]: more exciting and a lot more crisper. And you really found the like,

01:55:50.320 --> 01:55:55.680
[Guest]: Roland Barthes calls it the punctum of the image, right? So you found that that part of something.

01:55:56.880 --> 01:56:00.320
[Guest]: Yeah, I did a bit of revision in the first couple of chapters, definitely.

01:56:01.040 --> 01:56:04.720
[Guest]: There was no other way, because then it wouldn't have been of the same quality.

01:56:04.720 --> 01:56:07.840
[Amit Varma]: And what are you working on now? I mean, the book was came out?

01:56:07.840 --> 01:56:14.400
[Guest]: Yes, so the Remnants came out in 2017 in India, it came out in 2019 in the rest of the world.

01:56:16.000 --> 01:56:24.000
[Guest]: Since then, I have been working on a novel. In fact, that I finished in March this year.

01:56:24.000 --> 01:56:24.560
[Unknown]: Wow.

01:56:24.560 --> 01:56:30.640
[Guest]: Yeah, but it took me three years. And since then, I have been working since March,

01:56:30.640 --> 01:56:36.080
[Guest]: I have been working on a book on generational memory of partition. So putting together a lot

01:56:36.080 --> 01:56:40.080
[Guest]: of the interviews I've taken over the last three or four years with second or third generations

01:56:40.720 --> 01:56:48.400
[Guest]: of families who had witnessed partition, get a sense of what we have inherited from the event.

01:56:48.400 --> 01:56:57.200
[Guest]: And again, I think I embarked on this book, because I was looking for some answers as to how

01:56:57.200 --> 01:57:02.560
[Guest]: as to how younger people feel about partition, have they inherited pain, have they inherited

01:57:03.120 --> 01:57:09.360
[Guest]: curiosity? Is it loss? Is it anger? Is it just longing for a place that you may never see?

01:57:10.400 --> 01:57:17.040
[Guest]: And I think what I have through a lot of my conversations is just many more questions,

01:57:17.840 --> 01:57:24.720
[Guest]: many more questions, very nuanced questions on identity, on belonging, on religion,

01:57:24.720 --> 01:57:30.400
[Guest]: on the duality of people, and the possible versions that exist within the same person.

01:57:31.200 --> 01:57:36.720
[Guest]: And yes, of course, a lot of lingering pain in a lot of people. So that's, that's what I'm

01:57:36.720 --> 01:57:42.320
[Guest]: writing these days, because all the history on generational memory, having interviewed Indians,

01:57:42.320 --> 01:57:46.560
[Guest]: Pakistanis, Bangladeshis, and people from the diaspora.

01:57:47.440 --> 01:57:51.680
[Amit Varma]: I love reading this book, and I look forward to reading more of your work. And, you know,

01:57:51.680 --> 01:57:56.080
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you that I think this is really important work. For my listeners, I must tell

01:57:56.080 --> 01:57:59.760
[Amit Varma]: them it is not important in the sense of this, it's important for you to read this, but it's

01:57:59.760 --> 01:58:05.040
[Amit Varma]: boring, but it's important. But no, I love reading it. I was very moved by it. And I think it's a

01:58:05.040 --> 01:58:08.800
[Amit Varma]: book that everyone should read. And I look forward to your novel as well. Thank you so much for

01:58:08.800 --> 01:58:13.680
[Amit Varma]: coming on the show. I'll have to process all the things you said about conversation and learn to

01:58:13.680 --> 01:58:18.720
[Guest]: apply some of them myself. You know, I think that this was a very nuanced conversation in itself.

01:58:18.720 --> 01:58:23.600
[Guest]: And I mentioned earlier to you, I hadn't spoken about remnants in a long time, which means that

01:58:23.600 --> 01:58:27.920
[Guest]: some of the things that I am also saying are in retrospect, thinking about,

01:58:29.520 --> 01:58:33.600
[Guest]: because you know, I think that this kind of work, you grow up really fast, whether you like it or

01:58:33.600 --> 01:58:41.200
[Guest]: not. And I'm 30 years old now. And I feel like I'm 100. Because I just have to process so many

01:58:41.200 --> 01:58:47.840
[Guest]: other people's traumas, really. And you just there's a heaviness, you know, but when you

01:58:47.840 --> 01:58:55.280
[Guest]: think back on what you have achieved by doing this, it really feels like it has given, and I

01:58:55.280 --> 01:59:00.720
[Guest]: know that I'm saying this about my own book. So it's a bit like, I don't know, I guess it's a bit

01:59:00.720 --> 01:59:06.320
[Guest]: like, not a good practice. I don't know. But I know that it has encouraged more people to ask

01:59:06.320 --> 01:59:13.280
[Guest]: questions in their family. And that means that an organic archive of partition memory is beginning

01:59:13.280 --> 01:59:19.360
[Guest]: to be formed. And one of the things about partition is that because we don't talk about it,

01:59:19.360 --> 01:59:25.760
[Guest]: there is no archive of memory that remains. And when we compare it to events like the Holocaust,

01:59:25.760 --> 01:59:32.480
[Guest]: which is often done because of the sheer numbers, we see that Holocaust survivors have really

01:59:32.480 --> 01:59:38.080
[Guest]: shared stories. And now partition was way more complicated, of course, in the sense that there

01:59:38.080 --> 01:59:43.840
[Guest]: was no one person to take blame for what happened, because everyone was to blame at one point.

01:59:44.560 --> 01:59:49.760
[Guest]: But I think that we have not shared our stories, which means that in some way, our stories still

01:59:49.760 --> 01:59:55.040
[Guest]: don't belong to us, we need to voice them. And I know that Rembrandts has changed a bit of that.

01:59:55.040 --> 01:59:58.240
[Guest]: And it has moved things in the right direction. And of course, not just me,

01:59:58.880 --> 02:00:03.040
[Guest]: writers like Kavita Puri, and Anam Zakaria, and Urvashi Pitalia, and Ritu Menon

02:00:03.040 --> 02:00:08.800
[Guest]: also do similar things. And it is their efforts, as well as mine, that are steering things in the

02:00:08.800 --> 02:00:14.160
[Guest]: right direction. So I think the people who are listening to this podcast, if you have stories

02:00:14.160 --> 02:00:21.360
[Guest]: of partition or any hidden history in your family, start to ask questions. It's very...

02:00:21.360 --> 02:00:26.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I think that, you know, especially given all the resonances of that in these current times,

02:00:26.480 --> 02:00:33.200
[Amit Varma]: I think it's both almost sort of urgent to come to terms with all of that. But equally,

